WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.420
[Amit Varma]: What makes a city? On one hand, it is clear that people make a city. The way we live,

00:00:11.420 --> 00:00:16.280
[Amit Varma]: the things we do, the languages we speak, the food we eat, all the things we call culture.

00:00:16.280 --> 00:00:21.000
[Amit Varma]: At the same time, our streets and buildings aren't just functional constructions without

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.300
[Amit Varma]: meaning or impact. Embedded within the walls of our cities, travelling through the bylanes,

00:00:26.300 --> 00:00:31.500
[Amit Varma]: in the very air we breathe, is a deep history that shapes our culture and our cities. We

00:00:31.500 --> 00:00:38.160
[Amit Varma]: may be unaware of this history and yet it shapes us in so many unseen ways. Delhi is

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:43.000
[Amit Varma]: a particularly fascinating city in this regard because it is not just one city but many.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.600
[Amit Varma]: There have been 7 cities of Delhi, perhaps even 14 depending on which source you believe.

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:52.480
[Amit Varma]: These separate cities of Delhi are cities that have stood apart but that have also been

00:00:52.480 --> 00:00:58.960
[Amit Varma]: superimposed like layers forming a three-dimensional tapestry, one on top of the other. These different

00:00:58.960 --> 00:01:05.160
[Amit Varma]: cities have carried with them the DNA of various civilizations. Delhi is not just an Indian

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:10.940
[Amit Varma]: city but also a Turkish city, also a Persian city, also a British city. And this blend

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:18.800
[Amit Varma]: of influences from across the world into one organic complex beast makes Delhi also a quintessentially

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.880
[Amit Varma]: Indian city because what is India if not a delightful khichdi that contains all of the

00:01:23.880 --> 00:01:29.440
[Amit Varma]: world. I am an occasional visitor to Delhi and driving through these streets of relatively

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:35.600
[Amit Varma]: recent vintage, I often see these old monuments all around me, these repositories of our past

00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:43.800
[Amit Varma]: and I wonder, if these walls could speak, what stories would they tell?

