00:03:49.040 --> 00:03:54.600
[Amit Varma]: Rana, before we begin talking about your fascinating books and the work that you've done, tell

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:58.160
[Amit Varma]: me a little bit about yourself. Are you a Delhi person to begin with?

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:03.600
[Guest]: I'm Delhi's adopted daughter. I never lived in Delhi. I was brought up in Lucknow. I belong

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:09.080
[Guest]: to Aligarh. I did my schooling in Lucknow and then college in Aligarh. And after that,

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:15.440
[Guest]: after I got married, we lived in various cities all over the country, as far as Cochin and

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:20.960
[Guest]: Pune. And then we went to the Middle East. And it was really one of my trips from the

00:04:20.960 --> 00:04:26.480
[Guest]: Middle East to Delhi that something pulled me to it. And my daughter was living here,

00:04:26.480 --> 00:04:31.160
[Guest]: working here. And that's the first time I really came to Delhi, not as a point of transit,

00:04:31.160 --> 00:04:39.000
[Guest]: but as a visitor to Delhi. And I went to Mehroli on a heritage walk. And that's when something

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:43.880
[Guest]: inside me urged me to write about it, to document the history of Delhi.

00:04:43.880 --> 00:04:48.240
[Amit Varma]: And were you someone who is generally otherwise into the history of cities, like when you

00:04:48.240 --> 00:04:52.200
[Amit Varma]: lived in all these different cities? You know, did architecture draw you in? Did you notice

00:04:52.200 --> 00:04:56.160
[Amit Varma]: these things? I mean, the reason I ask is this almost naive question is because when

00:04:56.160 --> 00:05:01.720
[Amit Varma]: it comes to myself, a lot of the city around me, wherever I am, almost becomes invisible.

00:05:01.720 --> 00:05:06.560
[Amit Varma]: It's it's normalized. So I'm in my own cocoon. I could be, you know, at a cafe or at home

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:11.360
[Amit Varma]: or in my car, and I don't notice stuff around me. So have you always been a noticer or did

00:05:11.360 --> 00:05:16.320
[Amit Varma]: that start happening after you got interested in architecture has always fascinated me.

00:05:16.320 --> 00:05:21.800
[Guest]: I did my master's in history. And though I specialized in economic history, because I

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:27.640
[Guest]: was studying in Aligarh Muslim University. But after I finished my master's, and even

00:05:27.640 --> 00:05:33.440
[Guest]: before it was always monuments, which fascinated me, though I never at that point of time ever

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:39.080
[Guest]: thought I would be working on it so seriously. And I still remember, I think I was about

00:05:39.080 --> 00:05:44.240
[Guest]: 14 or 15 years old when I went to Fatehpur Sikri. And the mystique of that city, a city

00:05:44.240 --> 00:05:49.240
[Guest]: which was so alive yet so dead with nobody living there, you know, that city pulled me

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:56.680
[Guest]: to it. And at that time, I didn't know what it was, but I could feel something that there

00:05:56.680 --> 00:06:02.600
[Guest]: are some, you know, the there is a saying in Urdu, khe khandar bata rahe hain, khe maara

00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:08.120
[Guest]: shandaar thi. So that is what has always spoken to me whenever I've been to these monuments.

00:06:08.120 --> 00:06:12.960
[Guest]: People see them as ruins. I see them as places where people lived and laughed and lived and

00:06:12.960 --> 00:06:19.200
[Guest]: loved and that each of them has a story. Today, of course, there's nobody to tell the story.

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:24.720
[Guest]: So I just took it upon myself. Maybe it was a bit ambitious or whatever you can call it.

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:30.040
[Guest]: But I just thought that these stories through the books that have been written on them,

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:36.720
[Guest]: especially Delhi is very well documented. So I went to the 18th, 19th century Urdu books

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:42.800
[Guest]: and chronicles and I started documenting from there. Then all the gazettes and all the books

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:48.840
[Guest]: that have been written under the SI, the archaeological reports, all of them document Delhi's monuments

00:06:48.840 --> 00:06:54.840
[Guest]: during the 19th and the 20th century. So I used all of them. And from there, I unraveled

00:06:54.840 --> 00:07:01.760
[Guest]: the history of most of Delhi's monuments, I think. In my trilogy by now, I must have

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:04.680
[Guest]: covered at least three to four hundred monuments.

00:07:04.680 --> 00:07:10.880
[Amit Varma]: Wow. And monuments not just in the terms of covering the monuments, but placing them in

00:07:10.880 --> 00:07:16.080
[Amit Varma]: the context of history and all of that, which also really fascinated. Are you someone who's

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:18.440
[Amit Varma]: always been into history in that sense?

00:07:18.440 --> 00:07:22.720
[Guest]: Yes. History has always been my subject. And I was not after my master's. I've been teaching

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:27.360
[Guest]: history also. I taught it at a school level in the senior school, 8th, 9th and 10th. I

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:31.680
[Guest]: taught it in Jamshedpur. Then I taught it when I was in the Middle East. So I've been

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:34.040
[Amit Varma]: in touch with history and teaching history.

00:07:34.040 --> 00:07:37.680
[Amit Varma]: And there's this old cliche that goes like, for example, when people listen to some of

00:07:37.680 --> 00:07:42.360
[Amit Varma]: the episodes I've done with historians like, you know, our mutual friend Manu and Ira and

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:46.840
[Amit Varma]: Parvati and so on. And people often say that they make history so interesting. And in school,

00:07:46.840 --> 00:07:50.760
[Amit Varma]: it was so boring. Our teachers taught it so badly. And now I'm sitting with someone who

00:07:50.760 --> 00:07:56.920
[Amit Varma]: actually taught history in school. So what was your approach towards sort of then teaching

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:58.560
[Guest]: history like?

00:07:58.560 --> 00:08:06.400
[Guest]: I had wonderful teachers of history. So when I taught history, I tried to take it away

00:08:06.400 --> 00:08:12.560
[Guest]: from just the, you know, the dates. Most students are just told, you know, learn this date.

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:17.800
[Guest]: I tried to analyze it, which is what the way I was taught. That history is all about analyzing

00:08:17.800 --> 00:08:22.480
[Guest]: the events that happen and why they happen, not just mugging up the dates. So I would,

00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:25.640
[Guest]: of course, in school, I would give them the dates and I would give them the charts and

00:08:25.640 --> 00:08:30.280
[Guest]: I would give them these, you know, how to learn them. But I would also explain that

00:08:30.280 --> 00:08:34.960
[Guest]: what is so fascinating and interesting about the dates. And then that makes it come life

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:42.000
[Guest]: for the student and then they remember it. So I remember a student telling me that history

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:46.520
[Guest]: was never my subject. I taught him in class eight and sixth and seventh. He had already

00:08:46.520 --> 00:08:51.160
[Guest]: been doing it. And he said that history was never my subject. But now I think I'm going

00:08:51.160 --> 00:08:53.160
[Amit Varma]: to take it up further.

00:08:53.160 --> 00:08:57.680
[Amit Varma]: And you're possibly, you know, doing the same service to your writings today. Did it help

00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:02.680
[Amit Varma]: while you were doing historical research? Did it sort of help that you could read multiple

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:07.240
[Amit Varma]: languages very well? Like, you know, you even got a book of translated works from Urdu to

00:09:07.240 --> 00:09:12.200
[Amit Varma]: English and did more sources, therefore, come alive for you because you could read Urdu.

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:16.840
[Guest]: Urdu is the language that I read. And that also is an interesting journey because Urdu

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:22.040
[Guest]: also I had learned as a child and then, you know, my knowledge was very rusty. I relearned

00:09:22.040 --> 00:09:27.040
[Guest]: it because when I decided to start writing and I start, I have this forum called Shire

00:09:27.040 --> 00:09:33.160
[Guest]: running on Twitter. It's still running after 10 years almost. And in that, once I started

00:09:33.160 --> 00:09:37.600
[Guest]: that, I started learning Urdu to understand what Urdu poetry is all about, not just, you

00:09:37.600 --> 00:09:42.640
[Guest]: know, writing it in Roman, but what are the symbols, what is the thought behind the poet's

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:47.840
[Guest]: mind. And as I went deeper and deeper into it, then obviously you need to know Urdu.

00:09:47.840 --> 00:09:54.240
[Guest]: So I learned Urdu and relearned, I should say, a language which I had forgotten. And

00:09:54.240 --> 00:10:00.720
[Guest]: that then helped me when I shifted to history. And that has been a big asset to me because,

00:10:00.720 --> 00:10:05.880
[Guest]: as I said, one of the two very definitive books which have been written on Delhi, one

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:11.560
[Guest]: was in Urdu called Asaru Sanadev, which I translated. Another is a three volume book

00:10:11.560 --> 00:10:21.640
[Guest]: by Bashiruddin Ahmed written in 1917 or so called Delhi Darul Hukumat. So that is the

00:10:21.640 --> 00:10:25.720
[Guest]: book which I have used as a base because they describe a Delhi which is no longer there.

00:10:25.720 --> 00:10:31.480
[Guest]: A lot of, most of the monuments have been destroyed or are in ruins or whatever it is.

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:37.000
[Guest]: So I use that as a base to take the stories, some anecdotes from there, then do my own

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:42.120
[Guest]: research and then place it that, okay, something was here at that time, where has it gone?

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:48.200
[Guest]: And why has it disappeared? Or what was the way that people saw it in, say, in the event

00:10:48.200 --> 00:10:54.160
[Guest]: Sir Syed writes, he's writing it at the time of the Mughal Empire. So when he saw the Red

00:10:54.160 --> 00:11:01.280
[Guest]: Fort, he saw it as a working, living palace. We see it today just as a tourist place. So

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:05.960
[Guest]: then Bashiruddin Ahmed described it under the British. And he says that, you know, the

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:10.880
[Guest]: room, there's one room, the Khwabga, and he says the British have made this into a Mughal

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:15.960
[Guest]: room where you can come and savour the same delights of being a Mughal. So you have the

00:11:15.960 --> 00:11:20.320
[Guest]: same sitting arrangement and Shah Jahan's sabre kept there and, you know, the Bahadur

00:11:20.320 --> 00:11:24.200
[Guest]: Shah's hookah kept there, so you come and feel like a king. So these things made it

00:11:24.200 --> 00:11:29.080
[Guest]: very fascinating for me. And that is why in my book, the last book that's come out, Shah

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:33.840
[Guest]: Jahanabad, The Living City, I have not only described the ruins, I have also described

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:39.640
[Guest]: as what it would have been like, taking material from these books, which are trying to show

00:11:39.640 --> 00:11:44.160
[Guest]: that. And also, I translated another couple of books which talk about the culture and

00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:50.280
[Guest]: the people of those days. So I took from all these books to try and recreate a Delhi which

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:52.480
[Guest]: existed in those days.

00:11:52.480 --> 00:11:56.360
[Amit Varma]: And how was the experience that, okay, you go to this monument, and it's just an empty

00:11:56.360 --> 00:11:59.960
[Amit Varma]: tourist place and you look around and the first time you're seeing it as an outsider,

00:11:59.960 --> 00:12:03.960
[Amit Varma]: you're a tourist. And then you read a book like this, which, you know, makes it much

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:08.640
[Amit Varma]: richer and, you know, brings that era alive. And then you go back to that place. And, you

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:12.400
[Amit Varma]: know, does the whole city start meaning different things to you?

00:12:12.400 --> 00:12:17.800
[Guest]: So normally, when I go to my first visit, I don't read much about it, except whatever

00:12:17.800 --> 00:12:23.320
[Guest]: I know, because I want that first impression to be my impression. And I photograph everything,

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:29.040
[Guest]: I videograph it, so that, you know, I have everything there that, then I come back and

00:12:29.040 --> 00:12:33.080
[Guest]: then I read about it. And then when I read, I look at my photographs and see, okay, this

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:37.320
[Guest]: is what, you know, sometimes I've taken a photograph, which may not have meant anything

00:12:37.320 --> 00:12:41.400
[Guest]: at that time. But when I come back and read about it, then I realize, okay, this is what

00:12:41.400 --> 00:12:47.080
[Guest]: they're talking about. Then I go back. And then that is my final research of placing

00:12:47.080 --> 00:12:53.160
[Guest]: it. And like in the case of Shahjahanabad, because that, and Mehroli also before that.

00:12:53.160 --> 00:12:57.400
[Guest]: Shahjahanabad is where people are staying. Then I go and talk to the local people. And

00:12:57.400 --> 00:13:03.320
[Guest]: in Shahjahanabad, I've done a lot of interviews, which I have included where, what do the people

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:08.480
[Guest]: who are living there think about it? So in so many cases, they said that, you know, old

00:13:08.480 --> 00:13:14.200
[Guest]: people think of old Delhi only as a food capital, or they think of it as a place where, you

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:21.120
[Guest]: know, it is unsafe. So how do the residents who are living there for say 200, 300 years,

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:24.880
[Guest]: some of them who came with Shahjahanabad, some who came shortly after that, how do they

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:30.120
[Guest]: see their heritage? And how are they trying to preserve it? So I've tried to collect that

00:13:30.120 --> 00:13:35.600
[Guest]: also, because I wanted to put all that in one place as a record, document that.

00:13:35.600 --> 00:13:41.280
[Amit Varma]: And I guess in doing all this, one trap you've tried to avoid is a trap that writers may

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:47.160
[Amit Varma]: have of exoticizing the everyday. So you're writing about a place that is very old and

00:13:47.160 --> 00:13:51.800
[Amit Varma]: has this rich history. And you know, there is a trap of reading too much into it and

00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:56.480
[Amit Varma]: how you avoided sidestep that, of course, is by taking all these interviews and, you

00:13:56.480 --> 00:14:02.120
[Amit Varma]: know, speaking to kind of local people there, you know, do you often find that people who

00:14:02.120 --> 00:14:08.120
[Amit Varma]: are actually living in the midst of history, as it were, that they are kind of unaware

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:12.160
[Amit Varma]: of all that has happened around them? And is that a good thing or a bad thing?

00:14:12.160 --> 00:14:18.200
[Guest]: See, in Delhi, the problem is that we saw two exodus, especially in Shahjahanabad, we

00:14:18.200 --> 00:14:23.880
[Guest]: saw an exodus in 1857, there was displacement. And then again, when they did come back, these

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:28.000
[Guest]: people had lost their inheritance and lived a different life from what they had lived

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:33.440
[Guest]: under the Mughals. But the whole of Delhi saw displacement and a transfer of population

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:42.280
[Guest]: in 1947. So when you go to many places in Delhi, there used to be, say about 20-30 years

00:14:42.280 --> 00:14:47.600
[Guest]: ago, there was no sense of association of people who had migrated from Pakistan. For

00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:51.200
[Guest]: them, this was just a place where they had come and they were trying to make a living.

00:14:51.200 --> 00:14:56.540
[Guest]: But today's generation has grown up with these monuments. So the schoolchildren, for them,

00:14:56.540 --> 00:15:01.240
[Guest]: it is something that is a part of their heritage. And they are no longer longing for what they've

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:07.000
[Guest]: left behind, because they've seen only this, that's what they've grown up in. So for them,

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:13.140
[Guest]: that association is also a very important thing. So when I talk to them, in Shahjahanabad,

00:15:13.140 --> 00:15:18.400
[Guest]: the families that I talk to have been living there forever. So since Shahjahanabad was

00:15:18.400 --> 00:15:23.000
[Guest]: made, or maybe, you know, they are the sixth generation or seventh generation, fourth generation,

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.640
[Guest]: fifth generation. So for them, of course, it is something that is theirs. But say, when

00:15:29.640 --> 00:15:34.560
[Guest]: I did a book called The Forgotten Cities of Delhi, now where we are sitting in Hauz Khas,

00:15:34.560 --> 00:15:39.520
[Guest]: this was the second city of Delhi city made by Alauddin Khilji. Nothing of the original

00:15:39.520 --> 00:15:45.280
[Guest]: city remains except one or two monuments like the Chor Minar and the Idgaah that is here.

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:51.120
[Guest]: The people who are living here have no memory of the past. So for them, everything, they

00:15:51.120 --> 00:15:55.360
[Guest]: are probably just, you know, going past and wondering what is the strange looking monument.

00:15:55.360 --> 00:16:00.400
[Guest]: They don't know it. But if you go to a place where people have always lived and lived with

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:04.560
[Guest]: it, they know the history of it. Like say somebody in Shahjahanabad would know what

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:11.080
[Guest]: Jawa Masjid is all about. But somebody living in Hauz Khas would know that there is a Neeli

00:16:11.080 --> 00:16:16.520
[Guest]: Masjid here, which was built by a woman. And it's a functioning mosque even today. Not

00:16:16.520 --> 00:16:21.240
[Guest]: of course as big, but still a very pretty mosque. But I think they would just bypass

00:16:21.240 --> 00:16:25.440
[Guest]: it. They wouldn't, you know, care about it because it's not something which is something

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:31.320
[Guest]: that they've grown up with. Children are now interested. Like Chor Minar is something that

00:16:31.320 --> 00:16:35.960
[Guest]: is very fascinating because you can see holes and you have these stories. It's alleged that

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:42.280
[Guest]: because Alauddin Khilji was fighting the Mongol menace and he was a very trying to be, you

00:16:42.280 --> 00:16:47.480
[Guest]: know, discipline his army and take on it. So of course he had a lot of measures in place,

00:16:47.480 --> 00:16:52.960
[Guest]: some of them which were extremely extreme. And one of them was that anybody caught, you

00:16:52.960 --> 00:16:58.200
[Guest]: know, stealing or anybody even in weights and measures or anything like that, then they

00:16:58.200 --> 00:17:02.040
[Guest]: could have all kinds of extreme punishments, including cutting of hands and cutting of

00:17:02.040 --> 00:17:06.560
[Guest]: heads. And this Chor Minar is said to be the place where the heads would be hanged. So

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:12.920
[Guest]: this is a very macabre and interesting monument. So I think this is something maybe people

00:17:12.920 --> 00:17:19.640
[Guest]: living around it may be fascinated by. I have no idea. But whenever I've come here, you

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:25.680
[Guest]: know, like Firoz Shah Kotla is said to be the city that is the famous city of the Jinns.

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:30.880
[Guest]: It's the fifth city of Delhi, Firoozabad. And when you go there, you'll find lots of

00:17:30.880 --> 00:17:36.720
[Guest]: people on a Thursday coming from old Delhi. But the first time I went there and I told

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:41.720
[Guest]: I had come from Dubai and I took a taxi and asked my driver to take me to Firoz Shah Kotla.

00:17:41.720 --> 00:17:47.360
[Guest]: He took me to the stadium. And I said, nahi, yeh toh nahi hai. And he said, nahi, yeh hi

00:17:47.360 --> 00:17:54.560
[Guest]: Anil Kumble ne 10 wickets liya tha. So I said, no, that is another old monument where a king

00:17:54.560 --> 00:18:00.320
[Guest]: used to have a castle there. So he said, achha, let us look for it. So, you know, like people

00:18:00.320 --> 00:18:04.480
[Guest]: living in Delhi think of Firoz Shah Kotla. Of course, that stadium has been, I think,

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:09.400
[Guest]: renamed now. But they think of it only as a stadium where Anil Kumble took 10 wickets.

00:18:09.400 --> 00:18:14.200
[Guest]: They don't remember that this is the fifth city of Delhi. This is where Firoz Shah ruled

00:18:14.200 --> 00:18:21.640
[Guest]: from. But on a Thursday, you'll find that people of old Delhi, they come there in, you

00:18:21.640 --> 00:18:26.680
[Guest]: know, in, I think, in hundreds or thousands or whatever, they come there for their mannats

00:18:26.680 --> 00:18:30.920
[Guest]: that they make to the Jinns. And they'll come with pots of biryanis and zarda which they

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:35.760
[Guest]: distribute because their mannats have been or their vows have been fulfilled. So it speaks

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:40.400
[Guest]: differently to different people. My own driver, I asked him once, I said, you know, like,

00:18:40.400 --> 00:18:44.120
[Guest]: I have access because whenever I go there, sometimes I tell him, I said, you know, I'll

00:18:44.120 --> 00:18:48.360
[Guest]: be there for three, four hours and I can buy you a ticket. Would you like to come in? And

00:18:48.360 --> 00:18:54.080
[Guest]: he says, khandro mein kya rakha hai, madam? So he can never figure out why am I so fascinated

00:18:54.080 --> 00:19:01.680
[Guest]: by these ruins and why do I spend so much time in there? But on a Thursday, Firoz Shah

00:19:01.680 --> 00:19:06.320
[Amit Varma]: Kotla is just something else again. No, and it just struck me, I recorded yesterday

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:10.680
[Amit Varma]: with Madhavi Menon, who's written the book, Infinite Variety, The History of Desire in

00:19:10.680 --> 00:19:16.320
[Amit Varma]: India. And she was telling me about the Jamali Kamali tomb, which you also mentioned in your

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:20.400
[Amit Varma]: first book, Where Stones Speak. And it's so fascinating to me that that's, you know, known

00:19:20.400 --> 00:19:25.280
[Amit Varma]: as a gay Taj Mahal. And it's, you know, there's this whole history of how Jamali and Kamali

00:19:25.280 --> 00:19:30.320
[Amit Varma]: might have been same sex lovers or we don't know. And how the tomb has these characteristics

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:36.320
[Amit Varma]: of, you know, both the feminine flat surface on top and a sort of dome inside, which is,

00:19:36.320 --> 00:19:40.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, so these deeper resonances that they carry, are they sort of popularly known

00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:46.920
[Guest]: or do you think that is starting to happen? Jamali was a Sufi saint and he was a poet.

00:19:46.920 --> 00:19:53.120
[Guest]: He wrote some very beautiful poetry. And he was the son-in-law of another very famous

00:19:53.120 --> 00:19:59.640
[Guest]: saint, Suharwati saint, who is also buried nearby. And the identity of the second person

00:19:59.640 --> 00:20:04.880
[Guest]: is not known. So all these histories and all these legends have come much after him. None

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:10.520
[Guest]: of the contemporary histories mention anything about a Kamali. So these names, like when

00:20:10.520 --> 00:20:15.640
[Guest]: you go to Sultan Razia's grave, they'll tell you Razia Shazia ki grave hai, because the

00:20:15.640 --> 00:20:20.800
[Guest]: words rhyme. So there are two graves there, one is Razia, one is Shazia. Rajji Chajji,

00:20:20.800 --> 00:20:26.320
[Guest]: that is what it's called, the sisters. So Kamali rhymes with Jamali, but none of the

00:20:26.320 --> 00:20:31.880
[Guest]: contemporary historians talk of a Kamali or a relationship. There's been a book recently,

00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:37.680
[Guest]: I think about four or five years ago, there was a book on it, which I did read on that.

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:45.920
[Guest]: And we have no idea what the relationship actually was. And he lived inside that. So

00:20:45.920 --> 00:20:52.340
[Guest]: most of these tombs are places where the saints lived and then they were buried inside that.

00:20:52.340 --> 00:20:58.160
[Guest]: So it could possibly have been a relationship between the two of them, or he may have just

00:20:58.160 --> 00:21:03.120
[Guest]: been a disciple, because you do have cases of disciples and the relation between the

00:21:03.120 --> 00:21:09.760
[Guest]: Pir-e-Murshid, like Hazrat Ramuddin and Hazrat Amir Khosrow. It was very, very close. So

00:21:09.760 --> 00:21:15.040
[Guest]: it could be that also. Who were also, according to Madhavi, possibly same-sex lovers. Could

00:21:15.040 --> 00:21:18.840
[Guest]: be. That's what I'm saying. I don't say it wasn't that, but what I'm just saying is that

00:21:18.840 --> 00:21:23.320
[Amit Varma]: it has not been mentioned by anybody. So it could be like Padmavat, that it's just something

00:21:23.320 --> 00:21:28.680
[Guest]: that came up later. So you have, and you have a lot of romantic stories which come up, like

00:21:28.680 --> 00:21:35.920
[Guest]: for example, Razia. Now the story of her, when yesterday also I was talking to somebody

00:21:35.920 --> 00:21:42.540
[Guest]: and the Jamia people had, they had called me for a street lecture series. So I was talking

00:21:42.540 --> 00:21:47.080
[Guest]: to them about Razia and I said, how many of you, when you think of Razia, think of Himamalini?

00:21:47.080 --> 00:21:52.240
[Guest]: And almost every hand went up. So when we talk of Razia Sultan made by Kamalam Ruhi

00:21:52.240 --> 00:21:58.720
[Guest]: and we think of, you know, Himamalini and we think of Dharmendra. But in reality, none

00:21:58.720 --> 00:22:04.120
[Guest]: of the contemporary sources ever mention a relationship between the two. The only thing

00:22:04.120 --> 00:22:10.600
[Guest]: that is mentioned is that she made him the master of his, of tables. So one historian

00:22:10.600 --> 00:22:18.080
[Guest]: says that when he helped her to mount the horse, he put his arms under her, hands under

00:22:18.080 --> 00:22:24.960
[Guest]: her arms. Now he would do that the same for any other king, wouldn't he? She was wearing

00:22:24.960 --> 00:22:28.720
[Guest]: male clothes. She had taken off her veil. In fact, as you point out in your book, she

00:22:28.720 --> 00:22:32.960
[Guest]: was named Sultan Razia, not Razia Sultan. So he would have done the same for Iltutmush

00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:37.680
[Guest]: also. But why then don't we talk of a relationship between him and Iltutmush? Then why only a

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:43.600
[Guest]: relationship between him and Razia? So these are ways which stories come up, like the Padmavati

00:22:43.600 --> 00:22:50.800
[Guest]: story also. That has come up. Padmavati is an allegory for a Sufi story. So, of course,

00:22:50.800 --> 00:22:56.240
[Guest]: the Piramurid relationship was very, very close. And it was something very special.

00:22:56.240 --> 00:23:03.440
[Guest]: So what it exactly is, we have no idea. But he used to live in that. Sheikh Jamali used

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:08.960
[Guest]: to live inside that Gujarat. And when he died, he died in Gujarat and he had will that he

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:14.840
[Amit Varma]: should be buried there. And what I also find fascinating is not just that these stories

00:23:14.840 --> 00:23:20.760
[Amit Varma]: come up, which may not often be true, but it's worth then inquiring what is the instinct

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:25.040
[Amit Varma]: that leads to these stories being created and propagated and believed. Like they come

00:23:25.040 --> 00:23:29.060
[Amit Varma]: up because people want, there's something in there that attracts people and they want

00:23:29.060 --> 00:23:35.000
[Amit Varma]: to believe. Like there's another very interesting story which you mentioned in Where Stones

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:38.640
[Amit Varma]: Speak, which is about the Iron Pillar. And what you pointed out about the Iron Pillar

00:23:38.640 --> 00:23:43.880
[Amit Varma]: is that it is definitely Iltutmush we now know who got it from Udaipuri and then he

00:23:43.880 --> 00:23:48.920
[Amit Varma]: planted it again, so to say. But there's also a legend about Anangpal having made it in

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:52.960
[Amit Varma]: the first place. And then there's a legend about how it goes deep into the earth and

00:23:52.960 --> 00:23:57.880
[Amit Varma]: it rests on the head of a serpent. And I mean, it's a delightful story. And one then wonders

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:05.120
[Amit Varma]: that what's going on here, this mythologizing that is happening. And is it in some senses

00:24:05.120 --> 00:24:09.800
[Amit Varma]: a version of the politics of today where you want to claim a certain piece of history and

00:24:09.800 --> 00:24:12.400
[Amit Varma]: you want to change history to suit your ends?

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:18.560
[Guest]: Yes. And the best way to do it is through stories, through folk stories, through retelling

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:23.560
[Guest]: of the tale. So, and this, the story that you mentioned about the Iron Pillar, they

00:24:23.560 --> 00:24:29.120
[Guest]: say that is the reason for the name Delhi also, because the original name was Dhilli

00:24:29.120 --> 00:24:35.720
[Guest]: or Dhillika. So, they say, Killi to Dhilli bhai, Tomar bhai Matheen. So, they say, Dhilli

00:24:35.720 --> 00:24:40.520
[Guest]: jo hai, yeh wahan se aaya hai. And because the Arabs could not say Dha, so it became

00:24:40.520 --> 00:24:46.680
[Guest]: Delhi and Dhilli. So, these are stories which just fascinate me and I always put them down

00:24:46.680 --> 00:24:51.620
[Guest]: because I feel that people should know that this is a story, but it's a story.

00:24:51.620 --> 00:24:55.280
[Amit Varma]: Because as much as the history itself, the stories also reveal something because they

00:24:55.280 --> 00:24:58.440
[Amit Varma]: are just the fact that they've survived and they're believed.

00:24:58.440 --> 00:25:03.520
[Guest]: And oral stories also, because oral history is again a big source. And when I put it down,

00:25:03.520 --> 00:25:08.280
[Guest]: I always make sure that I write that this is oral history, this is a story. I have not

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:14.320
[Guest]: found any contemporary source to reinforce this, but this is there. So that, you know,

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:19.000
[Guest]: like, it's at least documented that these are stories. Some of the stories are so delightful

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:24.920
[Guest]: and some of the stories also, you know, they tell you about that age, of how did people

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:25.920
[Amit Varma]: think.

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:30.280
[Amit Varma]: Give me an example of stories you like.

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:35.920
[Guest]: So there's this story in one of the books that I've translated, That City of My Heart,

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:41.640
[Guest]: in that the first book, Adhilli Ka Akhari Didar, the story is being told, it's written

00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:47.640
[Guest]: by somebody else, Syed Wadi Hassan, but he has a narrator who's called Agai Begum. Now,

00:25:47.640 --> 00:25:53.600
[Guest]: Agai Begum lived as a Mughlani. Mughlani were the seamstresses and the ladies-in-waiting

00:25:53.600 --> 00:25:58.600
[Guest]: or whatever inside the Red Fort. So she stayed inside the Red Fort. Now, she's telling the

00:25:58.600 --> 00:26:03.880
[Guest]: story of how things happened when they lived in the, you know, when the Mughal kings were

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:09.520
[Guest]: there. And she describes the Phulwalo Ki Sehr. Now, Phulwalo Ki Sehr is a historical event

00:26:09.520 --> 00:26:16.000
[Guest]: and it still happens. And when she's describing it, she describes an anecdote, which she says

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:23.440
[Guest]: that, you know, like the Badshah would, how they would come all the way from the Red Fort

00:26:23.440 --> 00:26:28.360
[Guest]: and they would come there and then, kis tare se baagon mein pakwan bhakte the. And one

00:26:28.360 --> 00:26:34.480
[Guest]: of the stories is, I'm forgetting whether it is hers or it is theirs, because I translated

00:26:34.480 --> 00:26:39.800
[Guest]: four stories in that. There's another book story there called Tilai Maulana Ki Jhilke.

00:26:39.800 --> 00:26:47.440
[Guest]: In one of them, there's a story of how there was this woman seamstress and her daughter-in-law

00:26:47.440 --> 00:26:52.560
[Guest]: finds a stone, that Paras ka patthar, jisko alchemist stone kehte. And then, of course,

00:26:52.560 --> 00:26:58.080
[Guest]: she goes and then she calls Begum Zeenat Mahal and then she comes. And by that time the stone

00:26:58.080 --> 00:27:04.200
[Guest]: has got thrown away. So, you know, the story is, this is definitely not true, but she's

00:27:04.200 --> 00:27:10.200
[Guest]: recorded it. So, this story, I think, is in one of the, one of these short stories that

00:27:10.200 --> 00:27:16.280
[Guest]: I translated. So, it's a very fascinating story that when the story describes, now,

00:27:16.280 --> 00:27:20.480
[Guest]: the part of the alchemist stone may not be true, but the way then they describe how Begum

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:25.000
[Guest]: Zeenat Mahal is coming. Now, she's coming with the paan daan, with the hookah, everything

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:30.480
[Guest]: comes behind her. So, the entire story of that. Then the story of the Phulwalo Ki Seher

00:27:30.480 --> 00:27:36.760
[Guest]: ki ek shakur kukkad wale the, you know, he hookah leke jaate the. Then how he would go,

00:27:36.760 --> 00:27:42.080
[Guest]: how he would be so well-dressed and unka hookah jab jaata tha. And, you know, the entire bazaar

00:27:42.080 --> 00:27:47.520
[Guest]: scene of how people are the saying, in the, today when we go to Mehroli, of course, that

00:27:47.520 --> 00:27:53.160
[Guest]: Jharna is in a very bad state, but they are talking of diving competitions being held

00:27:53.160 --> 00:28:00.560
[Guest]: there, ke waha pe aam ka baag hai, us aam ke baag mein pakwan pakra hai, you know, dahi

00:28:00.560 --> 00:28:03.840
[Guest]: bade ban rahe hain, things like that, you know, and the varieties of alms and all that,

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:09.000
[Guest]: all this describes Andar Se Ki Goliya, which we still have. So, it's a continuity also.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:13.800
[Amit Varma]: So, it's a history told through stories and it's also stories about history and it's all

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:17.880
[Amit Varma]: of these melding together, which one of the interesting things which strikes me whenever

00:28:17.880 --> 00:28:24.840
[Amit Varma]: I read history is that sitting in the present time, looking at everything around us seems

00:28:24.840 --> 00:28:28.960
[Amit Varma]: to be filled with certainty. So, so many of us like the conception of Delhi, you know,

00:28:28.960 --> 00:28:33.320
[Amit Varma]: so most people, when they think of Delhi, they'll think of Lutyens Delhi, where, you

00:28:33.320 --> 00:28:37.400
[Amit Varma]: know, so many of us come, or if you think of old Delhi, you'll think of Shahjahanabad.

00:28:37.400 --> 00:28:42.080
[Amit Varma]: But Shahjahanabad is actually the second last Delhi in a series of many, many Delhi's and

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:46.800
[Amit Varma]: everything changes so fast. And all of what we know as reality is both contingent and

00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:52.520
[Amit Varma]: extremely recent. And how does it like, you know, when you're writing about Delhi in summer,

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:57.320
[Amit Varma]: all these Delhi's are sort of superimposed on each other. How did you develop the gaze

00:28:57.320 --> 00:29:02.080
[Amit Varma]: to be able to, you know, separate them out? So, as I said, that has been done according

00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:08.920
[Guest]: to Bashiruddin Ahmed's book and Sir Syed. Both of them have clearly demarcated it. So,

00:29:08.920 --> 00:29:13.120
[Guest]: and plus, you know, the historical, the saying of that this city was, which city was built

00:29:13.120 --> 00:29:18.320
[Guest]: by the Tughlaq. So, you have very clearly demarcated dynasties here. So, that has never

00:29:18.320 --> 00:29:23.040
[Guest]: been a problem because those monuments are very easy to get. They are all historically

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:30.920
[Guest]: documented. So, that is not a problem. It's, and most of the tombs that we see today, again,

00:29:30.920 --> 00:29:35.680
[Guest]: that was something that I learned from Bashiruddin Ahmed, that when the Lodhi's were ruling here.

00:29:35.680 --> 00:29:41.040
[Guest]: Now, before that, the slave kings or even the Khenjis and the Tughlaqs, they were from

00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:46.800
[Guest]: Turkic descent, but the Lodhi's were Afghans. Now, Afghans have a kind of a tribal system

00:29:46.800 --> 00:29:53.000
[Guest]: where each tribal king is as important as the next. So, earlier, while they could not

00:29:53.000 --> 00:29:58.320
[Guest]: have, each noble could not have such a lavish tomb, the Lodhi's could all have their own

00:29:58.320 --> 00:30:03.000
[Guest]: tombs. The only difference was that the king had an octagonal tomb and the rest of them

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:07.440
[Guest]: could have a tomb. So, Bashiruddin Ahmed says that there was a thriving business in tombs

00:30:07.440 --> 00:30:12.520
[Guest]: today, like we have flats. So, there would be tombs ready to sell and to be bought. And

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:17.640
[Guest]: that's the dynasty was overturned by the Mughals and some of the tombs got left and that is

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:22.280
[Guest]: why maybe they are empty today. So, you know, we think of, you know, life and death are

00:30:22.280 --> 00:30:26.600
[Guest]: so sacred and, you know, like so many of us are superstitious, but they were building

00:30:26.600 --> 00:30:31.280
[Amit Varma]: and selling tombs. Well, there won't have been multi-story tomb

00:30:31.280 --> 00:30:36.400
[Amit Varma]: blocks where there are apartment blocks, but that's, you know, so let's go back to the

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:40.680
[Amit Varma]: origins of Delhi. And this is, of course, disputed and some of it is even in the territory

00:30:40.680 --> 00:30:46.240
[Amit Varma]: of mythology and, you know, one is never quite sure whether Indaprastha, which is supposed

00:30:46.240 --> 00:30:51.000
[Amit Varma]: to be the first form of Delhi, sort of existed here. Now, you point out in one of your books

00:30:51.000 --> 00:30:57.320
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, every city needs basically three things, Darya, Badal or Hakim. So, expand

00:30:57.320 --> 00:31:01.080
[Amit Varma]: on this a little bit and then tell me what is the impetus behind sort of the early Delhi's

00:31:01.080 --> 00:31:03.320
[Amit Varma]: that are coming up? What are they? How do they come up?

00:31:03.320 --> 00:31:09.800
[Guest]: See, the first documented Delhi is the Tomar Delhi, of which the surviving monument is

00:31:09.800 --> 00:31:17.360
[Guest]: Surajkund. And they lived on what is today's Mehroli, the ridge. So, that was a defensive

00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:21.120
[Guest]: position that they took. It wasn't a very big city. So, they have reservoirs. There

00:31:21.120 --> 00:31:24.640
[Guest]: are remains of the reservoirs over there. So, strategic is the impetus.

00:31:24.640 --> 00:31:30.240
[Guest]: Strategic. So, for them, defense was of the most important thing. Then when the Delhi

00:31:30.240 --> 00:31:35.560
[Guest]: Sultans come and they defeat the Chauhans and they start living there, they also occupy

00:31:35.560 --> 00:31:40.760
[Guest]: that same space, that same Lalkot. So, there's one more thing I'd like to say. Many people,

00:31:40.760 --> 00:31:47.160
[Guest]: I've heard them and I've heard them on TV also say that Lalkala was built by the Tomar.

00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:52.200
[Guest]: There are definitely two red forts in Delhi, but the red fort of the Tomar is in Mehroli.

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:57.840
[Amit Varma]: And that's Lalkot. That's Lalkot. And this used to be called Qala-e-Mubarak. It was not

00:31:57.840 --> 00:32:03.920
[Guest]: called Lalkala. So, today we call it Lalkala, but this was made by Shah Jahan. And the Tomar

00:32:03.920 --> 00:32:08.040
[Guest]: Lalkot is in Mehroli. And there's a difference of 26 kilometers between the two. So, they

00:32:08.040 --> 00:32:15.000
[Guest]: are two separate cities, two separate buildings. So, the Tomars lived in Mehroli, in the Lalkot.

00:32:15.000 --> 00:32:21.240
[Guest]: And the Delhi Sultans came and also occupied the same space. And you have all the documents

00:32:21.240 --> 00:32:25.960
[Guest]: of Minhaj-e-Siraj and all those who are talking of crowning, coronations taking place inside

00:32:25.960 --> 00:32:31.560
[Guest]: that area, etc. We have a document of Sultan Razia being crowned over there, also in the

00:32:31.560 --> 00:32:37.040
[Guest]: Qutub complex. And they lived very close to that in Qasr-e-Firoza. There's a road running

00:32:37.040 --> 00:32:42.040
[Guest]: there, but that is where they live now. So, when we are talking of that, and then when

00:32:42.040 --> 00:32:47.240
[Guest]: the Mongols came, they attacked all of Central Asia. India is the only place where they were

00:32:47.240 --> 00:32:52.400
[Guest]: not successful because Alauddin Khalji took them on head on. And then he moves out of

00:32:52.400 --> 00:32:57.520
[Guest]: Lalkot and builds the second city of Siri. And that's heavily fortified. And where is

00:32:57.520 --> 00:33:03.240
[Guest]: that in current? Where we are sitting now? Houskhas. And Ishyat village. Ishyat village,

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:09.240
[Guest]: if you go, you will see the ruins of the walls and heavily fortified walls over there. So,

00:33:09.240 --> 00:33:14.040
[Guest]: you can see that. You can see the bastions. A lot of it has been, you know, like incredibly

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:18.320
[Guest]: thick walls. You talk of how there were these chambers where you could walk, the soldiers

00:33:18.320 --> 00:33:22.680
[Guest]: could walk in between. And so the change of guard. And everything would be preserved.

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:27.240
[Amit Varma]: And you talk about how, you know, there are accounts of black rice being taken, rice that

00:33:27.240 --> 00:33:32.320
[Amit Varma]: has turned black, but it's still perfectly eatable within those chambers. So, that is

00:33:32.320 --> 00:33:39.000
[Guest]: how Delhi kept this thing. And then Tughlaq Abad, when Qais-ud-Din Tughlaq made that,

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:43.600
[Guest]: and then he had to abandon it because of lack of water. They did make bubblies inside. And

00:33:43.600 --> 00:33:49.840
[Guest]: now there's this very famous story about, ya rahe gujar, ya rahe ujar. So, now Professor

00:33:49.840 --> 00:33:54.400
[Guest]: Muhammad Habib says that, you know, Hazrat Naam-ud-Din Auliya was not so petty as to

00:33:54.400 --> 00:33:58.800
[Guest]: be cursing like that. And there has to be some other reason about it. So, but this is

00:33:58.800 --> 00:34:04.720
[Guest]: the popular perception. We all say that Ras-ud-Din Tughlaq died because of a curse by Hazrat

00:34:04.720 --> 00:34:08.800
[Guest]: Naam-ud-Din Auliya, which he says is not true because there's nothing that bears, there's

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:13.480
[Guest]: nothing in history which says that, you know, there was this kind of enmity between them.

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:17.480
[Amit Varma]: So again, these are all stories. And also curses don't kill people.

00:34:17.480 --> 00:34:24.320
[Guest]: I have documented all that also. I've given, so I've tried to, what I've done is that I've

00:34:24.320 --> 00:34:28.760
[Guest]: given the popular perception as well as what the historical fact is, so that people can,

00:34:28.760 --> 00:34:31.440
[Amit Varma]: you know. In fact, you gave some 7-8 versions of how

00:34:31.440 --> 00:34:37.440
[Amit Varma]: the name Delhi came about. At one point, I got really confused. What's the one that you

00:34:37.440 --> 00:34:41.640
[Guest]: think is most likely? See, Dhillika was the name that came here.

00:34:41.640 --> 00:34:48.760
[Guest]: They say soft soil. The Singh, because the soil was soft, so it comes from that, Dhillika.

00:34:48.760 --> 00:34:53.240
[Guest]: And then again, because Dha is something that's not in the Arabic language, so it becomes

00:34:53.240 --> 00:35:00.240
[Guest]: Dilli. Dilli is colloquial and Dhilli is the court language, the used in the literary,

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:06.080
[Guest]: the Singh register. And now in the, and Hazrat-e-Dhilli is what it's called by Hazrat Amir Khosrow.

00:35:06.080 --> 00:35:11.600
[Guest]: And then when the British come, then as per their phonology, because L could, you know,

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:17.960
[Guest]: has to come after H, sorry, Delhi, yes, it has to come before, L has to come before H,

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:21.840
[Guest]: so it becomes, instead of Delhi, it becomes Delhi. Now, this is something that was pointed

00:35:21.840 --> 00:35:27.600
[Guest]: out to me by Shoaib Daniel, because he does a lot of work on languages and linguistics.

00:35:27.600 --> 00:35:31.200
[Guest]: So he's the one who told me about this, why it became Delhi from Delhi.

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:35.420
[Amit Varma]: Shout out to Shoaib, it's quite an insight. And just thinking aloud, it's also so interesting

00:35:35.420 --> 00:35:43.280
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, we don't just have to look at historical documents, or oral history even

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:47.960
[Amit Varma]: to figure out what history is, that in the modern times, there are so many ways of doing

00:35:47.960 --> 00:35:52.360
[Amit Varma]: it, like in Tony Joseph's book, for example, where you look at genetics, or like in this

00:35:52.360 --> 00:35:57.560
[Amit Varma]: case, we got a clue through language, through linguistics, and it's all of these different

00:35:57.560 --> 00:36:03.720
[Amit Varma]: sort of sciences and even arts coming together to shine a light on history. What's also kind

00:36:03.720 --> 00:36:09.800
[Amit Varma]: of interesting to me is that part of what happens as newer Delhi take over older ones

00:36:09.800 --> 00:36:17.000
[Amit Varma]: and newer rulers take over older ones, is that while there is, of course, this syncreticism

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:22.960
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, your culture is absorbing everything, there's also a lot of violence, and both going

00:36:22.960 --> 00:36:28.280
[Amit Varma]: side by side, in the sense that, you know, when Qutubuddin Abaq and Iltutmish and later

00:36:28.280 --> 00:36:32.040
[Amit Varma]: the Khiljis, and when they take over from the Tomars, there's a lot of destruction,

00:36:32.040 --> 00:36:37.200
[Amit Varma]: they destroy all the old temples, and they build the mosque instead. And yet the pillars

00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:41.160
[Amit Varma]: are actually made from the, like you pointed out, the pillars are those Hindu pillars,

00:36:41.160 --> 00:36:42.160
[Guest]: so to say.

00:36:42.160 --> 00:36:46.760
[Guest]: And the artisans would also be the same artisans, as one of the historians says, I'm forgetting,

00:36:46.760 --> 00:36:51.560
[Guest]: I think, one of the sources which I consulted, they said, it is possible that it would be

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:54.840
[Guest]: the same artisan who built the temple who's now building the mosque.

00:36:54.840 --> 00:36:58.880
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and it's all melting together. So, you know, the calligraphy has Hindu motifs, you've

00:36:58.880 --> 00:37:03.280
[Amit Varma]: pointed out, you know, you've pointed out similarly in the tomb of Iltutmish, how you

00:37:03.280 --> 00:37:08.960
[Amit Varma]: see this meld of influences. So, it's both that destruction is happening, and yet the

00:37:08.960 --> 00:37:14.880
[Amit Varma]: absorption of culture is happening. And, you know, later on, we see this replicated in

00:37:14.880 --> 00:37:19.480
[Amit Varma]: colonial times. You point out in your book about how when the British built the railway

00:37:19.480 --> 00:37:24.640
[Amit Varma]: lines, they destroyed the tomb of Zebun Nisar, Aurangzeb's daughter, and how Lutyens Delhi

00:37:24.640 --> 00:37:29.920
[Amit Varma]: was actually, you know, a large number of tombs, graves, pavilions, wells and mansions,

00:37:29.920 --> 00:37:34.080
[Amit Varma]: as you describe it, had to be demolished, sort of they entombed the tombs in a sense

00:37:34.080 --> 00:37:38.480
[Amit Varma]: under Lutyens Delhi. One can look back and one can see the changes, but a lot of these

00:37:38.480 --> 00:37:45.240
[Amit Varma]: changes were also accompanied by this sort of violence. Did that also have sort of social

00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:47.760
[Amit Varma]: implications which last to this day?

00:37:47.760 --> 00:37:55.360
[Guest]: So that is the part of the hakim. Dhaniya was when Firozabad, the fifth city of Delhi

00:37:55.360 --> 00:38:00.680
[Guest]: comes and is settled near on the banks of the Yamuna. That's the first city that comes

00:38:00.680 --> 00:38:04.960
[Guest]: on to the bank of the Yamuna because of water needs. And then, of course, Dinpanna, which

00:38:04.960 --> 00:38:09.040
[Guest]: is Purana Qila, and then Shahjahanabad, they're all on the banks of the Yamuna because big

00:38:09.040 --> 00:38:15.800
[Guest]: population you need water. And the hakims win them fancies. Now, which ruler doesn't

00:38:15.800 --> 00:38:20.760
[Guest]: rule by force? I'm talking of a ruler. I'm not talking of a democracy. I'm talking of

00:38:20.760 --> 00:38:27.560
[Guest]: a monarchy. Every monarch is by nature cruel, by nature forceful.

00:38:27.560 --> 00:38:31.640
[Amit Varma]: Even in a democracy, a state has a monopoly on violence. And that is always implicit.

00:38:31.640 --> 00:38:36.680
[Amit Varma]: For example, one interesting thing that struck me, which I was also going to ask you about

00:38:36.680 --> 00:38:41.440
[Amit Varma]: is, for example, how Lalkot is inside Sanjay one, which I presume is named after Sanjay

00:38:41.440 --> 00:38:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi. Yes. And that also, in a sense, is an act of violence that you're sort of, you

00:38:47.000 --> 00:38:52.240
[Amit Varma]: know, trying to reclaim a piece of the past by erasing it and by putting a contemporary

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:55.840
[Amit Varma]: name on it. And there are also these other juxtapositions happening, like you point out

00:38:55.840 --> 00:39:00.040
[Amit Varma]: in your book, how the remains of the Badaungate are at Kilarai, Pithora, which are at the

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:04.080
[Amit Varma]: Qutub Golf Club. So it's like, you know, the present takes over the past. But that's a

00:39:04.080 --> 00:39:08.200
[Amit Varma]: different matter as far as a sort of. But anyway, sorry, that's a digression.

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:15.960
[Guest]: Also, the first of all is that whoever, especially the medieval rulers, stamping your authority

00:39:15.960 --> 00:39:22.320
[Guest]: by the use of religion was always very effective because and it didn't necessarily mean that

00:39:22.320 --> 00:39:28.680
[Guest]: those people were using religion as a tool of ruling also. This was just to stamp their

00:39:28.680 --> 00:39:35.360
[Guest]: authority. So, you know, you dismantle the or you destroy a temple and you build a mosque.

00:39:35.360 --> 00:39:40.520
[Guest]: You've told the population or your new subjects that, OK, we are the kings here. It's our

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:46.400
[Guest]: rule that is going to be perpetuated or our rule that is going to be here now. So that

00:39:46.400 --> 00:39:49.800
[Guest]: is the first thing. The second thing is that when the rule, the

00:39:49.800 --> 00:39:54.800
[Guest]: Muhammad Ghori's army comes here and when Qutubuddinabad starts ruling, apart from the

00:39:54.800 --> 00:40:01.640
[Guest]: fact the symbolism of stamping their authority by destroying a temple and building a mosque.

00:40:01.640 --> 00:40:06.440
[Guest]: The second thing is they want to build a mosque in a hurry. Where do they get everything from?

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:12.640
[Guest]: So then you have the reuse. So you immediately reuse what you have destroyed and you deface

00:40:12.640 --> 00:40:18.000
[Guest]: it and you plaster. Originally, the Qutub Islam pillars were plastered. The plaster

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:23.960
[Guest]: has gone away now. So that is how you do it. And that is how they've always done it. And

00:40:23.960 --> 00:40:29.920
[Guest]: if you see, there's this new book that has come out by Richard Eaton, India in the Persianate

00:40:29.920 --> 00:40:35.440
[Guest]: age. He talks of two journeys and he talks, his book opens with the journey of Mehmood

00:40:35.440 --> 00:40:43.680
[Guest]: Ghazni coming to Somnath and Rajinder Chola going from the south to Bengal. And he says

00:40:43.680 --> 00:40:49.680
[Guest]: both the journeys are very similar and both of the journeys culminate in destroying the

00:40:49.680 --> 00:40:57.800
[Guest]: temple. But of course, Ghazni destroys the Shivling and the idol in Somnath, whereas

00:40:57.800 --> 00:41:03.040
[Guest]: the Chola Kings brings it back and installs it in his kingdom. So these are again stamping

00:41:03.040 --> 00:41:09.320
[Guest]: their authority via religion because he was of the same religion. He brought it and he

00:41:09.320 --> 00:41:14.600
[Guest]: brought it here, but he did not leave it there. And he does attack it. And so these are, you

00:41:14.600 --> 00:41:21.440
[Guest]: know, symbolism, which religion is a very big symbol. And that is why it's always been

00:41:21.440 --> 00:41:30.440
[Guest]: used as a tool of oppression, as a tool of sometimes, you know, like empowerment or sometimes

00:41:30.440 --> 00:41:36.680
[Guest]: to give power also to the people. Like we were talking of stories. One of my favorite

00:41:36.680 --> 00:41:43.400
[Guest]: stories is a book written by Faratullah Baig called Phoolwalon ki Sehr. I talk a lot about

00:41:43.400 --> 00:41:47.400
[Guest]: Phoolwalon ki Sehr because for me that symbolizes what Delhi was in the...

00:41:47.400 --> 00:41:49.000
[Guest]: Tell me a bit about Phoolwalon ki Sehr.

00:41:49.000 --> 00:41:56.000
[Guest]: Okay. So Phoolwalon ki Sehr starts in the 1820s. There's this ruler, Bahadur Shah's

00:41:56.000 --> 00:42:04.040
[Guest]: father, Akbar Shah II. Akbar Shah II has a son called Mirza Jahangir. Mirza Jahangir

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:12.960
[Guest]: was very a favorite of the king, obviously, and very impetuous. And he gets into a fight

00:42:12.960 --> 00:42:17.360
[Guest]: with the British resident. And that is the time when the British resident was ruling

00:42:17.360 --> 00:42:18.360
[Amit Varma]: Delhi.

00:42:18.360 --> 00:42:20.560
[Guest]: So he has to shoot the British resident, you pointed out, from the roof.

00:42:20.560 --> 00:42:26.360
[Guest]: Yes, he shoots at him. He calls him a Lulu. So then, of course, the seaton is told that

00:42:26.360 --> 00:42:30.520
[Guest]: Lulu means pearl and he's giving you a compliment. Of course, you know, Lulu means something

00:42:30.520 --> 00:42:36.240
[Guest]: else in Urdu and Hindi, which is the language was spoken by then. So he accepts it. Then

00:42:36.240 --> 00:42:38.240
[Guest]: he shoots at him and then he's exiled.

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:39.240
[Amit Varma]: And an orderly dies.

00:42:39.240 --> 00:42:44.400
[Guest]: An orderly dies and he's exiled and sent to Allahabad. And his mother then vowed that

00:42:44.400 --> 00:42:51.760
[Guest]: if he comes back, I will, you know, walk all the way to Qutubuddin Bakhtiar Kaki's Dargah

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:56.720
[Guest]: in Mehrauli and offer a chadar there. And then at that time, Akbar Shah says that, OK,

00:42:56.720 --> 00:43:01.600
[Guest]: if you're going there, then you must offer a chadar or a chhatr to the temple of Yogmaya.

00:43:01.600 --> 00:43:07.560
[Guest]: Yogmaya is Krishnaji's sister that got exchanged in the jail. So that is how it starts. And

00:43:07.560 --> 00:43:13.280
[Guest]: then earlier it would be that on a Thursday they would offer the chhatr on Yogmaya and

00:43:13.280 --> 00:43:17.640
[Guest]: on Friday they would take the chadar to the Dargah and that continued. And then the phool

00:43:17.640 --> 00:43:23.080
[Guest]: walon, it's called Sair-e-Gulfarosh because the flower vendors also, you know, scattered

00:43:23.080 --> 00:43:27.600
[Guest]: flowers all over the way. And then even today, if you see a lot of floral tribute is paid

00:43:27.600 --> 00:43:32.600
[Guest]: in any urs, you have a lot of flowers and a lot of floral tribute of the floral chadars

00:43:32.600 --> 00:43:45.120
[Guest]: and et cetera, et cetera. So Farhatullah Beg records a story of the Sair-e-Gulfarosh, which

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:50.520
[Guest]: happened in 1846 or something during the reign of Bahadur Shah Zafar. He's, of course, writing

00:43:50.520 --> 00:43:55.840
[Guest]: in 60s or 70s. And he talks of that time and he says that at the time, and of course, there

00:43:55.840 --> 00:44:01.400
[Guest]: was some power left with Bahadur Shah and he talks of it that, you know, like he's describing

00:44:01.400 --> 00:44:07.160
[Guest]: it and he says that the people come and they pass by Zafar Mahal, which is the palace,

00:44:07.160 --> 00:44:12.160
[Guest]: the summer palace of the Mughals and the balconies where they would come to watch the procession

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:17.640
[Guest]: going by. And he's asked to come to the Dargah. As I said, the Mandir was a day earlier and

00:44:17.640 --> 00:44:21.600
[Guest]: the next. And he says that I didn't go to the Mandir, so how can I go to the Dargah?

00:44:21.600 --> 00:44:27.840
[Guest]: My people will be so sad that the king didn't go to the Mandir and went to the Dargah. So

00:44:27.840 --> 00:44:34.120
[Guest]: he doesn't go to the Dargah because he has not been able to go to the Mandir as he was

00:44:34.120 --> 00:44:41.200
[Guest]: not well. So for me, this is what Delhi was. And this is what we keep talking of the Ganga

00:44:41.200 --> 00:44:46.640
[Guest]: Jamuni, Tehzeeb or the syncretism. This is what it was. And that is why everybody fought

00:44:46.640 --> 00:44:51.840
[Guest]: the first war of independence under Bahadur Shah Zafar's banner, even whether it was Nana

00:44:51.840 --> 00:44:59.040
[Guest]: Saheb or Tatya Tope or Laxmibai, it was all under his banner. And when we, this is, of

00:44:59.040 --> 00:45:03.760
[Guest]: course, a story which has been written some years later, but Zaheer Dehlvi, when he's

00:45:03.760 --> 00:45:09.280
[Guest]: writing Dastane Ghadar, he's writing it. He, of course, does also write it later on, but

00:45:09.280 --> 00:45:14.480
[Guest]: he was an eyewitness to all the things that were happening during the, what he calls the

00:45:14.480 --> 00:45:21.440
[Guest]: Ghadar. And he describes this incident, which happened much before 1857, where he says that

00:45:21.440 --> 00:45:27.040
[Guest]: one day Bahadur Shah, you know, like in the morning, they would give Jharokha Darshan

00:45:27.040 --> 00:45:33.000
[Guest]: and that balcony is still there. The Jamuna was over there in the morning, the Hindu ladies

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:38.160
[Guest]: and the men would come out for their snan and they would do the Ganga Snan and the other,

00:45:38.160 --> 00:45:41.920
[Guest]: the non-Hindus and the Muslims and all, they would come and they would all assemble under

00:45:41.920 --> 00:45:46.480
[Guest]: the Jharokha and they would come and see his face and then go about their daily business.

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:52.800
[Amit Varma]: Sounds like what happens outside Amitabh Bachchan's bungalow in Bombay.

00:45:52.800 --> 00:45:57.760
[Guest]: Something like that. So he comes there and he sees that on the bank of the Yamuna, there

00:45:57.760 --> 00:46:01.680
[Guest]: are these tents and he asks them, who are you and why are you here? He sends somebody

00:46:01.680 --> 00:46:05.440
[Guest]: there and he finds out that these are the butchers and they've been told by the British

00:46:05.440 --> 00:46:11.320
[Guest]: that you can no longer stay here because of the work you're doing. It's, you know, spoiling

00:46:11.320 --> 00:46:16.800
[Guest]: the city. And so he calls his, there's not much he can do. He cannot overturn the order.

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:19.320
[Guest]: So he calls his Wazir and he says,

00:46:19.320 --> 00:46:22.120
[Guest]: Mera Kheema bhi wahi laga do.

00:46:22.120 --> 00:46:26.560
[Guest]: And of course, the minute his Kheema goes there and he goes there and his tent is also

00:46:26.560 --> 00:46:31.960
[Guest]: pitched next to the butchers, the resident, the British resident comes running and says,

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:35.760
[Guest]: Huzoor, what are you doing? And he says, I have to stay with my people. He says, after

00:46:35.760 --> 00:46:40.240
[Guest]: I leave, you can do whatever you want. But as long as I'm there, I am with my people.

00:46:40.240 --> 00:46:46.440
[Guest]: And he says, he uses the analogy, he says, the flesh can never be separated from the

00:46:46.440 --> 00:46:53.400
[Guest]: nail. Naakhoon se ghosht alag nahin ho sakta hai. And he stays there. So that happens.

00:46:53.400 --> 00:47:00.880
[Guest]: And then we say that a few months down the line, the ghosis, that is the doodhwalas,

00:47:00.880 --> 00:47:04.440
[Guest]: the ghosis and the doodhwalas would, of course, the butchers would have been Muslim, but the

00:47:04.440 --> 00:47:08.160
[Guest]: ghosis and the doodhwalas would not have been Muslim. He said the same thing happened and

00:47:08.160 --> 00:47:12.400
[Guest]: they come and they also come and pitch that and then says that they've been asked to leave

00:47:12.400 --> 00:47:19.440
[Guest]: the city because of the, that whatever they're doing, the work is hampering the beautification

00:47:19.440 --> 00:47:23.400
[Guest]: of the city or whatever it is that the British are doing. So again, he says the same thing.

00:47:23.400 --> 00:47:27.400
[Guest]: Mera kheema wahi laga do. And he goes there and the British come. Then he says, you know,

00:47:27.400 --> 00:47:32.960
[Guest]: you cannot separate me from my people. And as long as I am here, my people will be with

00:47:32.960 --> 00:47:38.280
[Guest]: me. He says, after I go, tum eet se eet baja dena. Delhi ki eet se eet baja dena. Lekin

00:47:38.280 --> 00:47:45.200
[Guest]: jab tak main hoon, mere log mere saath rehenge. So this is how he treated his subjects. And

00:47:45.200 --> 00:47:51.120
[Guest]: when Zaheer Dahilvi is writing, the title that he gives is Badshaah ki Raiya Parwari.

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:58.440
[Guest]: That how he treated his subjects. Equal, always. So, you know, these and I see no reason not

00:47:58.440 --> 00:48:01.880
[Guest]: to believe what Zaheer Dahilvi is writing because he would have been an eyewitness.

00:48:01.880 --> 00:48:06.640
[Guest]: He was the Badshaah's courtier. So he would be going there. He was a kind of a page. So

00:48:06.640 --> 00:48:11.000
[Guest]: he would be going there every day. And he was also his a poet. So he would go there

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:15.520
[Guest]: with his verse and all that. So he would have seen everything that was happening. So this

00:48:15.520 --> 00:48:23.440
[Guest]: is the kind of Delhi that there was in the late, say in the 1840s, 1830s, 1840s, 1850s

00:48:23.440 --> 00:48:27.720
[Amit Varma]: till 1857. And the tragedy of history is that eventually

00:48:27.720 --> 00:48:33.360
[Amit Varma]: he did leave the city on the British, as you can say, eat, say it like, you know, and that

00:48:33.360 --> 00:48:36.880
[Amit Varma]: happened. And it's also interesting here, you know, going back to that earlier theme

00:48:36.880 --> 00:48:42.040
[Amit Varma]: about how stories are propagated and myths are made to suit political purposes, that,

00:48:42.040 --> 00:48:47.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, I grew up learning in school that Bahadur Shah Zafar was a very, you know, ineffectual,

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:52.280
[Amit Varma]: weak sort of ruler. And these sort of statesman like qualities are just not part of those

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:57.800
[Amit Varma]: stories. And it all kind of depends on who's telling those stories and where they have

00:48:57.800 --> 00:49:03.740
[Amit Varma]: come from. How would you tease out issues of reliability? Because a lot of sources are

00:49:03.740 --> 00:49:07.640
[Amit Varma]: people who are close to the protagonists. Some might be writing two centuries after

00:49:07.640 --> 00:49:12.160
[Amit Varma]: what has happened when you can't be sure whether they'll be correct. In fact, for a certain

00:49:12.160 --> 00:49:16.760
[Amit Varma]: period, you point out that most of the sources are Turkish or Persian sources, there aren't

00:49:16.760 --> 00:49:22.120
[Amit Varma]: so many Indian sources about the lives of those sultans. So how does that exercise happen?

00:49:22.120 --> 00:49:25.920
[Amit Varma]: Because if someone's writing the history of something that happened in the 20th and 19th

00:49:25.920 --> 00:49:29.680
[Amit Varma]: century, I guess there are enough sources that you can collate them all and get a very

00:49:29.680 --> 00:49:34.200
[Amit Varma]: good sense. But if you're writing about something that happened in the 12th century or the 11th

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:35.200
[Guest]: century.

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:40.720
[Guest]: So that is also an area of concern that most of the histories that were written of the

00:49:40.720 --> 00:49:47.640
[Guest]: Delhi sultans, obviously, they were in Persian, and they were translated by Eliot and Dawson

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:54.640
[Guest]: as history of India as told by its historians. And as many historians have pointed out, they

00:49:54.640 --> 00:49:58.920
[Guest]: focused only on one aspect of the rulers because they were trying to show that the British

00:49:58.920 --> 00:50:03.920
[Guest]: are the rulers who've come as saviors of the Indians. So you have a lot of commentaries

00:50:03.920 --> 00:50:08.520
[Guest]: written on those histories also that this is where they've misinterpreted it, this is

00:50:08.520 --> 00:50:14.800
[Guest]: where they've gone wrong. So anyone who's a serious student of history goes through

00:50:14.800 --> 00:50:21.040
[Guest]: the commentaries also to see what is there. You go through more than one translation.

00:50:21.040 --> 00:50:25.760
[Guest]: I don't know Farsi myself, although of course I read. So Farsi, I have to go through more

00:50:25.760 --> 00:50:30.440
[Guest]: than one translation. Sometimes I have to go and see the translations, how they've been

00:50:30.440 --> 00:50:35.960
[Guest]: used and mentioned by other historians, historians whom I rely on and find credible. And as far

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:41.640
[Guest]: as the Zaheer Dahalvi is concerned, now he ran from pillar to post hiding from the British.

00:50:41.640 --> 00:50:47.160
[Guest]: So his escape is a very, very interesting part of the journey apart from the story of

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:53.520
[Guest]: the Ghadar itself. And when he's writing it on his deathbed, he is living in British India.

00:50:53.520 --> 00:51:00.680
[Guest]: So for him to be praising the king who has been exiled by the British, it was an act

00:51:00.680 --> 00:51:07.160
[Guest]: of bravery and it was also an act of resistance. So I see no reason why he would be, you know,

00:51:07.160 --> 00:51:14.280
[Guest]: like coloring it because that's why I feel that the history that was written either in

00:51:14.280 --> 00:51:20.560
[Guest]: the 19th century or in the, by ordinary people, I'm not talking of court histories, or in

00:51:20.560 --> 00:51:25.960
[Guest]: the late 19th century, early 20th century, there was at that time, not that agenda. See,

00:51:25.960 --> 00:51:31.680
[Guest]: we are not, we don't have a right or a left or a centrist or, you know, there's no secular

00:51:31.680 --> 00:51:36.000
[Guest]: history and liberal history and, you know, religious history kind of those angles that

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:40.360
[Guest]: are given to us, the names that we are given today, they are just writing things as they

00:51:40.360 --> 00:51:45.560
[Guest]: see it and as they perceive it. So those histories, of course, are colored by a little bit of

00:51:45.560 --> 00:51:49.720
[Guest]: whatever their feelings are, but there's much more truth in what they're writing when they're

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:52.880
[Amit Varma]: describing the society. At least they won't sort of get the basic

00:51:52.880 --> 00:51:58.160
[Guest]: facts wrong. Even if the facts are not there, actually the thought that they're describing

00:51:58.160 --> 00:52:00.960
[Guest]: has to be there because where else do they get it from?

00:52:00.960 --> 00:52:05.040
[Amit Varma]: Fair point. Let's, let's take a quick commercial break and talk more about the history of Delhi

