00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:43.320
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen. I'm chatting with Rana Safi, the outstanding historian

00:53:43.320 --> 00:53:49.040
[Amit Varma]: of Delhi and Delhi's monuments. She's written a fabulous trilogy, which sort of puts all

00:53:49.040 --> 00:53:54.400
[Amit Varma]: of Delhi's archaeology into historical context and architecture into historical context.

00:53:54.400 --> 00:54:01.760
[Amit Varma]: And what also struck me in a question I had while reading it is that, you know, just as

00:54:01.760 --> 00:54:06.400
[Amit Varma]: people make the architecture around them, can architecture also shape the people who

00:54:06.400 --> 00:54:11.520
[Amit Varma]: live there? Like, can architecture itself, the nature of the architecture, shape a society?

00:54:11.520 --> 00:54:16.560
[Guest]: Let's take the example of Jama Masjid. I think it does shape. Even today, it's a symbol of,

00:54:16.560 --> 00:54:22.880
[Guest]: you know, old Delhi, like when you had this, the recent protest marches that you had, the

00:54:22.880 --> 00:54:30.560
[Guest]: Bhim Ami Chandrashekhar Azad, he started it from Jama Masjid in 1900 and I think 11 or

00:54:30.560 --> 00:54:37.360
[Guest]: 14, whatever it was just during the British period. He's asked by the Imam to come and

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:42.080
[Guest]: deliver a lecture from the member of the Jama Masjid. And Kishtilu is given the keys of

00:54:42.080 --> 00:54:49.400
[Guest]: the Golden Temple and asked to, you know, go there. So this kind of importance and exchange

00:54:49.400 --> 00:54:55.120
[Guest]: because of the importance of the building. So yes, definitely, Jama Masjid is a masjid,

00:54:55.120 --> 00:54:59.280
[Guest]: it's a mosque and it plays a very important part in the roles of the believers, but it's

00:54:59.280 --> 00:55:04.240
[Guest]: also a symbol of Delhi. And that is why it was confiscated after 1857 by the British.

00:55:04.240 --> 00:55:09.040
[Guest]: It took a long time and a lot of negotiation for them to get it back. So it was seen as

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:13.480
[Guest]: a symbol. So of course, architecture also does shape people and history.

00:55:13.480 --> 00:55:18.120
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, a quick bit of trivia for my listeners, Swami Shraddhanand, in fact, was

00:55:18.120 --> 00:55:23.160
[Amit Varma]: also, his name was Munshi Ram and he was, in fact, given the title of Mahatma before

00:55:23.160 --> 00:55:28.480
[Amit Varma]: Gandhi himself was. So in a sense, he was the Mahatma before the Mahatma. And this speech

00:55:28.480 --> 00:55:33.040
[Amit Varma]: that he gave at the Jama Masjid is considered a great iconic moment because to call a Hindu

00:55:33.040 --> 00:55:40.160
[Amit Varma]: leader like that to speak at the Jama Masjid was sort of an example of that Hindu-Muslim

00:55:40.160 --> 00:55:42.640
[Amit Varma]: sort of relationship getting so much better at the time.

00:55:42.640 --> 00:55:47.040
[Guest]: And they say that when he finished, there were, you know, sounds of Hindu-Muslim Ekta

00:55:47.040 --> 00:55:54.080
[Guest]: Zindabad all over the mosque. And then again in 1947, after partition, Maulana Abul Kalam

00:55:54.080 --> 00:55:57.960
[Guest]: Azad speaks to the Muslims from there and tells them not to migrate. And he said, this

00:55:57.960 --> 00:56:03.200
[Guest]: is your country. So again, that is again a very iconic speech where he talks of what

00:56:03.200 --> 00:56:08.680
[Guest]: India means for the Muslims and why they should stay back here. So, yes, it has shaped, it

00:56:08.680 --> 00:56:14.000
[Guest]: has been a very important part of Delhi and of people's history.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:18.360
[Amit Varma]: So tell me more about the other Delhi's, you know, in the sense that, first of all, how

00:56:18.360 --> 00:56:21.840
[Amit Varma]: many Delhi's were there? Because you have also given different versions in your book

00:56:21.840 --> 00:56:27.400
[Amit Varma]: where you have said maybe there were 14, maybe there were seven. And all I could really register

00:56:27.400 --> 00:56:31.960
[Amit Varma]: was that, okay, the last two are Shahjahanabad, which we call Old Delhi and Lutyens Delhi,

00:56:31.960 --> 00:56:36.000
[Amit Varma]: which we call New Delhi. And of course, you know, you have Tomar's Delhi, but I don't

00:56:36.000 --> 00:56:41.280
[Amit Varma]: know where to place that in the numbering. And, you know, so take me through the, you

00:56:41.280 --> 00:56:43.720
[Amit Varma]: know, all the Delhi's that are sort of emerging.

00:56:43.720 --> 00:56:48.560
[Guest]: So the seven cities of Delhi, I think is a very romantic idea that's come from the seven

00:56:48.560 --> 00:56:53.440
[Guest]: cities of Rome. Okay, because you have this book by Gautam Hearn, which is called the

00:56:53.440 --> 00:56:59.440
[Guest]: seven cities of Delhi. So it's very obviously, you know, inspired by that. But when Sir Sayyed

00:56:59.440 --> 00:57:05.440
[Guest]: is talking, he talks, and even when Bashiruddin Ahmed is talking, they start with Indraprasth.

00:57:05.440 --> 00:57:10.960
[Guest]: So and they say that, you know, this is a mythological city, excavations are still going

00:57:10.960 --> 00:57:11.960
[Amit Varma]: on to prove it.

00:57:11.960 --> 00:57:12.960
[Amit Varma]: But there's no proof.

00:57:12.960 --> 00:57:19.600
[Guest]: As yet not, but they're still excavating. So after that, then the first reference that

00:57:19.600 --> 00:57:27.280
[Guest]: we have that Delhi, there was a thing Delhi is in 250 BC, you have Ashoka edict. It's

00:57:27.280 --> 00:57:32.720
[Guest]: a minor edict, but in East of Kailash, you find it. But the fact that no Buddhist text

00:57:32.720 --> 00:57:39.520
[Guest]: mentions a city called Delhi or Dehlu or whatever or Delhi or anything resembling the present

00:57:39.520 --> 00:57:44.480
[Guest]: name means that it wasn't anything much because they are talking of Mathura where they are

00:57:44.480 --> 00:57:48.920
[Guest]: going, but they're not talking of this area. So the first references we really get are

00:57:48.920 --> 00:57:57.680
[Guest]: from the Tomars, which is 1059, you point out as 726 is the time when Tomars come and

00:57:57.680 --> 00:58:03.360
[Guest]: Lalkot is settled by Anangpal in the 10th century.

00:58:03.360 --> 00:58:06.400
[Amit Varma]: You know, there's an interesting anecdote you share about the Indraprastha times where

00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:11.400
[Amit Varma]: you talk about how Yudhishthira one day uncovered his food and he found a fly in the food and

00:58:11.400 --> 00:58:15.400
[Amit Varma]: he said enough, you know, this is I want purity and I don't want this and then he goes off

00:58:15.400 --> 00:58:19.360
[Amit Varma]: and lives in the Himalayas. And I, you know, when I read that, I just thought of, you know,

00:58:19.360 --> 00:58:25.000
[Amit Varma]: the air in Delhi today and what Yudhishthira would kind of think of it. So what would you

00:58:25.000 --> 00:58:31.520
[Amit Varma]: date as a first Delhi, then the city established by Tomar and then by Lalkot, that's the documented

00:58:31.520 --> 00:58:37.360
[Amit Varma]: history. The first documented city of Delhi is Lalkot.

00:58:37.360 --> 00:58:42.240
[Guest]: And that's, you know, again, Aravalli Hills because strategic reasons and all of that.

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:46.920
[Guest]: Then in between, like I've given in my first book, I've given 14 cities. Now these cities,

00:58:46.920 --> 00:58:53.400
[Guest]: they were the cities like you have Khizrabad and you have various rulers made their capitals,

00:58:53.400 --> 00:59:00.040
[Guest]: Kilukdi and all that, but they were not as such very big cities. They were more of the

00:59:00.040 --> 00:59:06.640
[Guest]: places of where they lived and places developed around them. So a fully developed city as

00:59:06.640 --> 00:59:12.360
[Guest]: in with its everything of its own are these seven.

00:59:12.360 --> 00:59:17.320
[Amit Varma]: And around what time does Delhi become really significant? Because again, you know, today

00:59:17.320 --> 00:59:21.680
[Amit Varma]: we think of Delhi as India's capital and always such a great city and all that. But as you

00:59:21.680 --> 00:59:26.040
[Amit Varma]: point out that in the early centuries of the millennium, travellers would not even mention

00:59:26.040 --> 00:59:30.200
[Amit Varma]: Delhi if they were travelling through the area, they talk about Mathura and whatever,

00:59:30.200 --> 00:59:33.840
[Amit Varma]: but Delhi never got a mention. Mathura was seems like the big like cosmopolis of the

00:59:33.840 --> 00:59:39.000
[Amit Varma]: age. Around what time does Delhi start to become politically significant and as a city

00:59:39.000 --> 00:59:40.000
[Guest]: it grows?

00:59:40.000 --> 00:59:44.920
[Guest]: See, after the invasion of the of Muhammad Ghori, because even Pirthi Raj Chauhan was

00:59:44.920 --> 00:59:51.160
[Guest]: ruling from Ajmer. He gets it from his grandfather. He gets Delhi, the Kingdom of Delhi from his

00:59:51.160 --> 00:59:57.920
[Guest]: grandfather Anangpal Thomas, but his capital is Ajmer. So it's only when the Delhi Sultans

00:59:57.920 --> 01:00:02.840
[Guest]: come here and they make it their capital and they start expanding from here, they expand

01:00:02.840 --> 01:00:08.840
[Guest]: their kingdom. That is when Delhi really becomes an important city. And then in between, of

01:00:08.840 --> 01:00:15.680
[Guest]: course, the Mughals, they go to Agra and then it comes back with Shah Jahan brings the capital

01:00:15.680 --> 01:00:18.280
[Amit Varma]: of the empire back to Delhi.

01:00:18.280 --> 01:00:22.800
[Amit Varma]: And you know, when you sort of look at the history of Delhi as a historian, do you watch

01:00:22.800 --> 01:00:27.240
[Amit Varma]: out for the danger of romanticizing the past?

01:00:27.240 --> 01:00:33.600
[Guest]: You know, yes, you know, when I first started writing, I had not learned the craft of writing

01:00:33.600 --> 01:00:39.600
[Guest]: or anything like that. I just wrote very, you know, as it came to me. So these are things

01:00:39.600 --> 01:00:45.560
[Guest]: which I never realized that I'm doing or not doing. It's only when the reviews of my first

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:49.640
[Guest]: book came out and I was very surprised, you know, somebody wants to review my book. And

01:00:49.640 --> 01:00:54.240
[Guest]: then they talked about this. It's only after two or three books that I realized that these

01:00:54.240 --> 01:00:59.440
[Guest]: are the traps that I should not fall into. I hadn't been doing it. But yes, romanticizing

01:00:59.440 --> 01:01:04.000
[Guest]: is something that comes very naturally to somebody who is looking up to a particular

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:10.080
[Guest]: period or a particular place or a particular monument. But that is a trap that a historian

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:11.080
[Amit Varma]: should not fall into.

01:01:11.080 --> 01:01:13.080
[Guest]: What are the other traps?

01:01:13.080 --> 01:01:18.080
[Guest]: Of being biased. These two things I have to be very careful about. Not to be biased, to

01:01:18.080 --> 01:01:24.640
[Guest]: try and put everything as carefully as I can. And, you know, like let the reader make their

01:01:24.640 --> 01:01:29.200
[Guest]: own choices based on whatever evidence that you are giving. And the other is, of course,

01:01:29.200 --> 01:01:34.320
[Guest]: not to romanticize, though that is something that's a little difficult. But bias is something

01:01:34.320 --> 01:01:39.560
[Guest]: which I am very careful about, that my own biases should not come into the book. I am

01:01:39.560 --> 01:01:45.320
[Guest]: a documenting history, so I have to document it as faithfully as I can.

01:01:45.320 --> 01:01:49.480
[Amit Varma]: And that's also complicated, isn't it? Because there's always a trade-off, I think historians

01:01:49.480 --> 01:01:54.960
[Amit Varma]: have, you know, tend to be careful of, where on the one hand, you want to chronicle faithfully

01:01:54.960 --> 01:01:59.720
[Amit Varma]: and let the facts speak for themselves. But on the other hand, if you just chronicle without,

01:01:59.720 --> 01:02:04.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, it becomes dry. So if you're giving perspective, that perspective will necessarily

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:05.560
[Guest]: come from you and what you bring to the person.

01:02:05.560 --> 01:02:10.960
[Guest]: Then it should be my opinion. It should not be given as a blanket opinion. So these are

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:15.280
[Guest]: things that you have to be careful about. We must not be judgmental. That's another

01:02:15.280 --> 01:02:20.640
[Guest]: thing that has to be, you know, because when you're writing about history, something which

01:02:20.640 --> 01:02:25.920
[Guest]: happened say 500 years ago, a thousand years ago, we cannot judge them according to today's

01:02:25.920 --> 01:02:31.600
[Guest]: standards. And that is something which is happening very often today. We say, for example,

01:02:31.600 --> 01:02:37.280
[Guest]: say we would judge what Pitsviraj Chauhan did, or Akbar did, or Aurangzeb did, or Ashoka

01:02:37.280 --> 01:02:43.880
[Guest]: did. We can't judge them by what is happening today, or by how we behave today. They behaved

01:02:43.880 --> 01:02:48.160
[Guest]: as they did according to the circumstances of the age they lived in. And that is why

01:02:48.160 --> 01:02:52.880
[Guest]: I said this book by Richard Eaton, India in the Persianate Age, is a very good book because

01:02:52.880 --> 01:02:58.000
[Guest]: it places everything exactly the way it is, and how you should look at it, how you should

01:02:58.000 --> 01:02:59.000
[Guest]: look at history.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:03.160
[Amit Varma]: In fact, that's a dilemma that keeps coming up, especially in this modern age, where we

01:03:03.160 --> 01:03:10.000
[Amit Varma]: are so quick to pass judgment on the past. And this is not even like the old past of

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:16.040
[Amit Varma]: Babur, it's the recent past, we just keep passing judgment based on contemporary values.

01:03:16.040 --> 01:03:22.320
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I sort of get from reading history is how it humanizes these people for

01:03:22.320 --> 01:03:27.160
[Amit Varma]: me. Like, you know, in Ira McCarty's history, for example, I learned about, you know, there's

01:03:27.160 --> 01:03:32.320
[Amit Varma]: a scene she describes about how, when the women in Babur's family are brought to Delhi,

01:03:32.320 --> 01:03:37.040
[Amit Varma]: and he is so excited to meet his wife, that he runs out of the palace barefoot and, you

01:03:37.040 --> 01:03:41.320
[Amit Varma]: know, runs out on the street, which an emperor is not supposed to do. And suddenly this person

01:03:41.320 --> 01:03:46.800
[Amit Varma]: who is otherwise caricatured as a brutal emperor who demolished temples and all of that, and

01:03:46.800 --> 01:03:51.920
[Amit Varma]: this sort of this human aspect to him. And it's interesting that, you know, when you're

01:03:51.920 --> 01:03:56.360
[Amit Varma]: writing about sort of, you could say in a very dry way that you're writing about architecture,

01:03:56.360 --> 01:04:00.760
[Amit Varma]: you're writing about buildings, but you're also writing about people. And, you know,

01:04:00.760 --> 01:04:06.520
[Amit Varma]: how did the way that you look at the city change as you started, you know, delving deeper

01:04:06.520 --> 01:04:07.520
[Guest]: into it?

01:04:07.520 --> 01:04:13.160
[Guest]: So, it's the, if I'm looking at a monument, that monument has been made by someone. So,

01:04:13.160 --> 01:04:18.800
[Guest]: what was the reason for that? Like, say, Humayun's tomb, for example, it's made by his wife,

01:04:18.800 --> 01:04:24.000
[Guest]: it's made by his eldest wife. His favorite wife is Hamida Bano Begum. But the tomb is

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:28.840
[Guest]: not made by his favorite wife, it's made by his eldest wife, who was also his cousin and

01:04:28.840 --> 01:04:32.680
[Guest]: with whom he did not really get along well, because she was very opinionated and very,

01:04:32.680 --> 01:04:37.480
[Guest]: you know, like, wasn't afraid to speak her mind. So, but it's she who makes the tomb,

01:04:37.480 --> 01:04:41.200
[Guest]: she who stays there and makes it her life mission to look after it. So, that's something

01:04:41.200 --> 01:04:45.520
[Guest]: very important that, you know, like, when we think of it today, that we would say, you

01:04:45.520 --> 01:04:50.720
[Guest]: know, like, Hamida Bano is the favorite wife, she is a wife who's very opinionated, who's,

01:04:50.720 --> 01:04:56.720
[Guest]: you know, not afraid to speak her mind. So, when we think, and Akbar, the son, is Hamida

01:04:56.720 --> 01:05:02.720
[Guest]: Bano's son. So, he's the ruler. So, he's the one who's giving the funds or whatever

01:05:02.720 --> 01:05:06.200
[Guest]: it is that, you know, it would, logically, everybody would think it's Hamida Bano who

01:05:06.200 --> 01:05:11.120
[Guest]: should be making this tomb, but it's not. It's Haji Begum, Bega Begum, who's making

01:05:11.120 --> 01:05:15.760
[Guest]: it. So, for me, that is, again, something very interesting, that why is it that she's

01:05:15.760 --> 01:05:22.600
[Guest]: making the tomb and not Hamida Bano? So, and there's a lot of confusion at times, people,

01:05:22.600 --> 01:05:26.120
[Guest]: that's why I've discussed it in my book, that, you know, it is not Hamida Bano, it is Haji

01:05:26.120 --> 01:05:30.800
[Guest]: Begum, and Haji Begum was Bega Begum, who was the eldest wife. That is she who's making

01:05:30.800 --> 01:05:35.480
[Guest]: the tomb, and, you know, that's so fascinating. And even in a, say, let's say, talk about

01:05:35.480 --> 01:05:41.120
[Guest]: the, or Qutub Minar, because that, again, is something very fascinating, that the Qutub

01:05:41.120 --> 01:05:46.880
[Guest]: Minar had only four stories, and there's a lightning strike, and the third one, the top

01:05:46.880 --> 01:05:51.800
[Guest]: one falls off, and when Feroz Shah repairs it, he makes one more. Today's conservationists,

01:05:51.800 --> 01:05:56.760
[Guest]: if they were to do anything like that, their heads would roll. But when he's doing it,

01:05:56.760 --> 01:06:00.800
[Guest]: he decides, okay, I must have something here also, so he makes two more, two, he makes

01:06:00.800 --> 01:06:06.080
[Guest]: it five. So, these are things which are very fascinating, that when you're making, how

01:06:06.080 --> 01:06:11.360
[Guest]: the person who's making it is trying to perpetuate his memory also, along with looking, conserving

01:06:11.360 --> 01:06:19.440
[Guest]: what is there. And the names, like, this was called Mazina, or the Mohsen's Tower. Saab,

01:06:19.440 --> 01:06:24.600
[Guest]: they say, the Qutub Minar, the word is first used in the 17th, 18th century by a British

01:06:24.600 --> 01:06:30.440
[Guest]: called Ensign Blunt. And the story is that the Qutub Saab ki laat hai, because a Sufi

01:06:30.440 --> 01:06:36.120
[Guest]: saint is supposed to have a staff, which connects him to heaven. And because Qutub Saab is such

01:06:36.120 --> 01:06:40.760
[Guest]: an important saint for Mehroli, in fact, they say the name Mehroli comes from his meher

01:06:40.760 --> 01:06:45.200
[Guest]: or his blessing. So, of course, he has to have a laat, which touches the heavens. So,

01:06:45.200 --> 01:06:50.560
[Amit Varma]: Qutub Minar becomes his laat. And this is something people often assume the Qutub Minar

01:06:50.560 --> 01:06:55.080
[Amit Varma]: is named after Qutubuddin Aibak, but of course, it's named after Khwaja Qutubuddin Bakhtiyar

01:06:55.080 --> 01:07:00.480
[Amit Varma]: Kaki. And you also told a delightful story about where the Kaki part of the name comes

01:07:00.480 --> 01:07:05.840
[Guest]: from. So, kindly, kindly tell. So, that is a story that, you know, like, all Sufi saints

01:07:05.840 --> 01:07:10.920
[Guest]: were, jisko faqirana ek zindagi kehte the, asli mein faqirana zindagi, us tariki zindagi

01:07:10.920 --> 01:07:16.640
[Guest]: jeete the, they would never, especially the Sishti saints, would never keep any money

01:07:16.640 --> 01:07:21.680
[Guest]: for themselves, even when they got gifts and futu, any kind of gifts that had to be distributed

01:07:21.680 --> 01:07:27.200
[Guest]: the same day. So, they were always living a hand-to-mouth existence. And Hazrat Bakhtiyar

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:35.080
[Guest]: Kaki's wife has to borrow money or has to be in debt for the bread that she's taking.

01:07:35.080 --> 01:07:39.680
[Guest]: And so, there are two versions to that. So, one is that, you know, he tells her that,

01:07:39.680 --> 01:07:44.240
[Guest]: you know, I'm not going to give you any more credit. And so, Bakhtiyar Kaki says that,

01:07:44.240 --> 01:07:48.640
[Guest]: you know, it doesn't matter. It will come to you. And then, of course, the bread starts

01:07:48.640 --> 01:07:53.200
[Guest]: coming, appearing every day for them in a shelf. So, these are his miracles and how

01:07:53.200 --> 01:08:01.160
[Guest]: the name Bakhtiyar comes, that ikhtiyar jiska hai. So, you know, like, and I am, you know,

01:08:01.160 --> 01:08:05.840
[Guest]: very attached to the Khutub Sahib because I feel he had a big role to play in my coming

01:08:05.840 --> 01:08:11.000
[Guest]: to Delhi. I feel that, you know, I had nothing to do with Delhi. As I said, Delhi has adopted

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:17.160
[Guest]: me. I never lived here. I wasn't from Delhi. But when I came to Delhi in 2012 and I went

01:08:17.160 --> 01:08:21.040
[Guest]: to his dargah, there's something that pulled me to Delhi. And after that, I've been coming,

01:08:21.040 --> 01:08:25.640
[Guest]: I was living in Dubai. My husband was in Dubai. I just packed my bag. He said, OK, you want

01:08:25.640 --> 01:08:31.280
[Guest]: to go there? You want to write? That's OK. So, I packed our luggage, got a container,

01:08:31.280 --> 01:08:36.200
[Guest]: booked the container. He shifted to a flat. I packed the villa and I came here and shifted

01:08:36.200 --> 01:08:40.520
[Guest]: here. And then I started living here. Something which I'd always thought that I would never

01:08:40.520 --> 01:08:46.120
[Guest]: ever live in Delhi or NRC. We had always thought that when we retire, we'd live in Pune because

01:08:46.120 --> 01:08:49.360
[Guest]: we'd spent 15 years in Pune and where we had a house.

01:08:49.360 --> 01:08:55.680
[Amit Varma]: And Pune is, of course, a very charming city where I studied. Are you then able to articulate

01:08:55.680 --> 01:08:59.360
[Amit Varma]: what it was about, you know, this that brought you back?

01:08:59.360 --> 01:09:05.000
[Guest]: No, this is something that cannot be put in words because Sufism is in something I've

01:09:05.000 --> 01:09:10.560
[Guest]: been, you know, like as a Shia, I've been going to Imam Bada's and to Raza's, which

01:09:10.560 --> 01:09:16.880
[Guest]: is of the Prophet and the Imams, Hazrat Ali and his children. I've been going to that

01:09:16.880 --> 01:09:23.840
[Guest]: since childhood. I visited almost all the Raza's in Iran, Iraq, Syria and Saudi Arabia

01:09:23.840 --> 01:09:28.760
[Guest]: and in India. And so that was something I've been doing. But Sufism wasn't something that

01:09:28.760 --> 01:09:33.120
[Guest]: I was connected to, though Hazrat Ali is said to be the first Sufi. So for me, you know,

01:09:33.120 --> 01:09:38.480
[Guest]: like it was more as a, you know, the Shia part of it rather than the Sufism part of

01:09:38.480 --> 01:09:44.640
[Guest]: it, that was something that I'd been connected to. So it's only when I came in 2012, I started

01:09:44.640 --> 01:09:50.480
[Guest]: going on walks with Asif the Helvi, who runs Delhi Karwan. So he lives in Mehroli and he

01:09:50.480 --> 01:09:55.760
[Guest]: is the one who started talking to me about Sufism. And he took me to Qutub Sahib Targah

01:09:55.760 --> 01:10:00.160
[Guest]: and there's something there that, you know, then drew me to Sufism. And today I like,

01:10:00.160 --> 01:10:05.040
[Guest]: of course, I can't say I'm a Sufi because that is a very long journey. But there's something

01:10:05.040 --> 01:10:11.320
[Guest]: about Sufism that attracts me, the simplicity of that. And I feel it's a natural corollary

01:10:11.320 --> 01:10:18.080
[Guest]: of since I'm a great believer of Hazrat Ali, that Hazrat Ali and Sufis all take, as I said,

01:10:18.080 --> 01:10:23.000
[Guest]: they take their chart, their descent from Hazrat Ali. So I feel that it's a very natural

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:31.160
[Guest]: journey for me to be able to coming from Ali to the Sufis of Delhi. So there's something

01:10:31.160 --> 01:10:36.800
[Guest]: about it. I can't explain it, but I feel that it is Qutub Sahib who asked me to stay in

01:10:36.800 --> 01:10:42.480
[Guest]: Delhi and to, you know, write about Delhi. And you also mentioned that you started learning

01:10:42.480 --> 01:10:48.600
[Amit Varma]: Urdu again, rediscovering Urdu as it were. And so through this process of sort of figuring

01:10:48.600 --> 01:10:52.280
[Amit Varma]: out the history of Delhi, and you're also obviously reading a lot of Urdu sources at

01:10:52.280 --> 01:10:58.400
[Amit Varma]: this time, you're translating these Urdu books on Delhi. Did that sort of deepen your appreciation

01:10:58.400 --> 01:11:06.400
[Amit Varma]: for Urdu literature and culture? And also, is there a sort of Urdu renaissance happening?

01:11:06.400 --> 01:11:10.440
[Amit Varma]: Like I also see Rekhta happening and more and more people are getting interested in

01:11:10.440 --> 01:11:11.440
[Guest]: it.

01:11:11.440 --> 01:11:15.440
[Guest]: The renaissance that's happening in Urdu is only in the spoken language and the poetry.

01:11:15.440 --> 01:11:20.880
[Guest]: It's not happening in the script. Because people who do want to speak, see we've always

01:11:20.880 --> 01:11:30.120
[Guest]: spoken in North India, we've spoken Hindustani, which is a soft version of Urdu itself, using

01:11:30.120 --> 01:11:38.920
[Guest]: a lot of Persian and Hindi words in it. But script, very few people know, and the script

01:11:38.920 --> 01:11:45.640
[Guest]: is dying. And when the script dies, the literature and the history dies. And in that sense, I

01:11:45.640 --> 01:11:51.320
[Guest]: would not say it's a renaissance. Because further, a language isn't only about poetry.

01:11:51.320 --> 01:11:56.240
[Guest]: A language is about, of course, a lot of the literature is again translated into English,

01:11:56.240 --> 01:12:01.280
[Guest]: but then you lose the nuance. And what about the history that's written in that? As I said,

01:12:01.280 --> 01:12:10.000
[Guest]: there's so much of history in that language. And there are so many, we are losing the dialects.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:17.000
[Guest]: We're losing Urdu on a daily basis. So the Rekhta is also only promoting the poetry.

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:22.760
[Guest]: The biggest service that Rekhta is doing, to my mind, is that they have digitalized

01:12:22.760 --> 01:12:27.240
[Guest]: all the old Urdu text. So they are there, but then you have to know the script to be

01:12:27.240 --> 01:12:32.400
[Guest]: able to read them. So, of course, they're there for scholars, but the common person

01:12:32.400 --> 01:12:40.080
[Guest]: has, they're running classes also. But it's, you know, as a language, unless you know the

01:12:40.080 --> 01:12:45.000
[Guest]: script, the language is in danger.

01:12:45.000 --> 01:12:49.360
[Amit Varma]: And one question that's always struck me when I've read something translated from one language

01:12:49.360 --> 01:12:53.680
[Amit Varma]: to another, when I happen to understand both of them, you know, is translation even possible?

01:12:53.680 --> 01:12:58.360
[Amit Varma]: It seems to me that languages are fundamentally so different from each other, that in a sense,

01:12:58.360 --> 01:13:03.040
[Amit Varma]: you are having to recreate the essence of something. You can't just translate word-to-word.

01:13:03.040 --> 01:13:05.640
[Amit Varma]: What was your process of learning how to translate like?

01:13:05.640 --> 01:13:10.840
[Guest]: As I said, again, I started translating without giving much thought to it. And the first book

01:13:10.840 --> 01:13:15.720
[Guest]: that I translated was Daftane Qadar. And that is, again, a very interesting story. I was

01:13:15.720 --> 01:13:20.480
[Guest]: reading the last Mughal by Dalrymple, and he says that the book called Daftane Qadar,

01:13:20.480 --> 01:13:24.400
[Guest]: and I'm surprised nobody's translated it. I said, okay, let me try that. So I took the

01:13:24.400 --> 01:13:28.400
[Guest]: book and I started. So the first thing was to get a copy of it, because I didn't have

01:13:28.400 --> 01:13:33.840
[Guest]: a very good print over here in, couldn't find a very good print of it in Delhi. So anyway,

01:13:33.840 --> 01:13:40.120
[Guest]: I was in Dubai, so I could get a print from Pakistan, then I got one from Raza Library.

01:13:40.120 --> 01:13:49.600
[Guest]: So I started with that. Now, I think there was recently a debate on Faiz. So on that,

01:13:49.600 --> 01:13:54.200
[Guest]: also something that I was talking, I mentioned that in a couple of my tweets and something

01:13:54.200 --> 01:14:00.040
[Guest]: that I've written, that any language, any literature depends heavily on the religious

01:14:00.040 --> 01:14:04.960
[Guest]: iconography of the language that it's writing on. Say, for example, P.G. Wodehouse, I'm

01:14:04.960 --> 01:14:09.880
[Guest]: a big P.G. Wodehouse fan. But when you read P.G. Wodehouse, if you do not know your Bible,

01:14:09.880 --> 01:14:13.760
[Guest]: if you do not know your hymns, you will not understand all the psalms. You don't understand

01:14:13.760 --> 01:14:18.080
[Guest]: half of what he's writing. You know, like he'll keep referring as pants the heart when

01:14:18.080 --> 01:14:24.040
[Guest]: heated in the chase. Now that's a hymn. So you have to know all that to be able to understand

01:14:24.040 --> 01:14:29.080
[Guest]: what he's talking about. So we don't call, you know, these are references which you've

01:14:29.080 --> 01:14:34.960
[Guest]: grown up with. So similarly, when you're translating from the language, so for Urdu, so though

01:14:34.960 --> 01:14:39.680
[Guest]: Urdu, I was still a work in progress, but the culture was something I was very invested

01:14:39.680 --> 01:14:45.760
[Guest]: in. I knew everything about that, the culture and the language and the religion. So that

01:14:45.760 --> 01:14:51.280
[Guest]: was the biggest challenge was how to translate that. Like in one place, Zaheer Dahilvi writes

01:14:51.280 --> 01:14:59.160
[Guest]: in one of the descriptions of Doomsday is that the sun will be a yard and a quarter

01:14:59.160 --> 01:15:03.680
[Guest]: above your head. So you have to know that. So when you're writing that, so when you're

01:15:03.680 --> 01:15:08.320
[Guest]: describing it, unless you know the reference. Now, somebody who doesn't know the Quranic

01:15:08.320 --> 01:15:14.240
[Guest]: reference to how Doomsday is described, and that is what is there in one of Faiz's poem.

01:15:14.240 --> 01:15:21.440
[Guest]: He describes it exactly the way it's given in the Quran, you know, the fluffs of the saying

01:15:21.440 --> 01:15:27.200
[Guest]: what's going to happen on Doomsday. So when you're invested in that language, in the culture

01:15:27.200 --> 01:15:32.560
[Guest]: and the religion, you're able to use that iconography. So that whichever language, whichever

01:15:32.560 --> 01:15:38.200
[Guest]: writer you're doing it. So when you are doing it, translation for me, it's not how good

01:15:38.200 --> 01:15:44.360
[Guest]: you are in the language itself. It's how good you understand, how well you understand the

01:15:44.360 --> 01:15:51.560
[Guest]: nuances. Like one very interesting anecdote. I did a lot of reading for translating Dastanikadar

01:15:51.560 --> 01:15:55.320
[Guest]: to understand what he's trying to do because I've given a lot of notes in that so that

01:15:55.320 --> 01:15:59.800
[Guest]: people understand what is happening because he's writing it and at times it's erratic

01:15:59.800 --> 01:16:04.040
[Guest]: and so that, you know, you understand completely what he's writing. And I wanted that to be

01:16:04.040 --> 01:16:09.400
[Guest]: there instead of just translation. So there in one place he mentions, when he's talking

01:16:09.400 --> 01:16:15.520
[Guest]: of, and all these platoons and regiments from all over the place are coming to Delhi to

01:16:15.520 --> 01:16:24.000
[Guest]: fight against the British. So he says, Now I kept looking at all the maps everywhere.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:28.400
[Guest]: I asked people, I said, where is the Safar Meena? Nobody could tell me, there's no place

01:16:28.400 --> 01:16:34.160
[Guest]: called Safar Meena. So then finally, I had a whole lot of questions, which I marked and

01:16:34.160 --> 01:16:38.840
[Guest]: for me, any questions I have in Urdu, I go to Professor Shamsur Rahman Farooqui. So he

01:16:38.840 --> 01:16:42.240
[Guest]: was coming to Delhi, he told me, so whatever you have, you just bring all your questions

01:16:42.240 --> 01:16:47.640
[Guest]: to me and we'll sit and discuss them. This was before it was the final edit. So I took

01:16:47.640 --> 01:16:51.280
[Guest]: it to him and then of course he told me this, this, this and then I asked him, I said, Sir,

01:16:51.280 --> 01:16:59.800
[Guest]: where is Safar Meena? So he started laughing. He said, that's sappers and miners. So that

01:16:59.800 --> 01:17:04.000
[Guest]: because he, and he told me, he said, you know, even I have wondered where it was, but then

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:08.560
[Guest]: because he had read somewhere and he could correlate that, you know, sappers and miners

01:17:08.560 --> 01:17:13.800
[Guest]: had come there and so he had read it in some other book somewhere. And then recently somebody

01:17:13.800 --> 01:17:18.000
[Guest]: else told me that in Bengal, there was a sapper and miner regiment and that place was called

01:17:18.000 --> 01:17:24.520
[Guest]: Safar Meena. So, you know, this is how, that is why it's so difficult at times. If this

01:17:24.520 --> 01:17:29.040
[Guest]: is a very simple thing, I could have written Safar Meena there, but then it wouldn't have,

01:17:29.040 --> 01:17:32.720
[Guest]: you know, the reader wouldn't have understood what is this Safar Meena. They would have

01:17:32.720 --> 01:17:38.160
[Guest]: also wondered like me, Safar Meena hai kidar? You know, things like this, when you're translating,

01:17:38.160 --> 01:17:45.720
[Guest]: like whenever I was translating Asaru Sanadeet. Now Asaru Sanadeet is in two editions. There

01:17:45.720 --> 01:17:51.400
[Guest]: are two editions of it. The first edition is written in 1846 and the second one is in

01:17:51.400 --> 01:17:57.440
[Guest]: 1854. And the first one is written when he writes, he writes, Sir Syed writes it in a

01:17:57.440 --> 01:18:03.080
[Guest]: very Persianized style. The second one is, of course, very, it's a simple Urdu one. So

01:18:03.080 --> 01:18:07.960
[Guest]: I started when I did it because I was using it for my own work when I was just writing

01:18:07.960 --> 01:18:13.520
[Guest]: the Delhi trilogy. So I was referring to the second edition only. And I had translated

01:18:13.520 --> 01:18:20.600
[Guest]: most of it for my own notes. And then I said, OK, why not, you know, translate this book?

01:18:20.600 --> 01:18:24.800
[Guest]: And then while I was translating that, I came to know that there is another edition and

01:18:24.800 --> 01:18:29.160
[Guest]: that's much more interesting. So that had all the anecdotes and all the spicy stories

01:18:29.160 --> 01:18:35.720
[Guest]: and everything. So then I hunted for that. I got a copy of that. And the monuments or

01:18:35.720 --> 01:18:39.400
[Guest]: something which are very easy for me because I had visited all the monuments that he talks

01:18:39.400 --> 01:18:43.920
[Guest]: about the 130 monuments. I knew them inside out. So when whatever he's talking about,

01:18:43.920 --> 01:18:48.360
[Guest]: I could understand what he's saying. But then there is a chapter in that which is Dilli

01:18:48.360 --> 01:18:55.040
[Guest]: Aur Dilli Ke Log. Now, that chapter is supposed to be one of the most important chapters of

01:18:55.040 --> 01:19:00.960
[Guest]: that book, which he hasn't included in the second edition. Now, this chapter was very,

01:19:00.960 --> 01:19:06.240
[Guest]: very Persianized Urdu. And in that he talks about, he gives each and every person that

01:19:06.240 --> 01:19:14.240
[Guest]: he gives them titles. Those were, you know, they just sailed over my head. So I had a

01:19:14.240 --> 01:19:19.920
[Guest]: Mufti Sahib who would help me with the Persian part of it because he knew Persian and Arabic.

01:19:19.920 --> 01:19:23.800
[Guest]: So I called him and I said, whenever I had a problem with Persian and Arabic, I would

01:19:23.800 --> 01:19:30.200
[Guest]: call him. So he came and I said, he started reading and, you know, there's no punctuation

01:19:30.200 --> 01:19:37.520
[Guest]: mark in the book. So it was Xerox of the time. I hadn't even got a, you know, a fresh copy.

01:19:37.520 --> 01:19:43.560
[Guest]: So we just could not figure out what are they saying? Where does one title end? Where does

01:19:43.560 --> 01:19:48.960
[Guest]: the second end? So then I started sending it, taking, you know, screenshots, sending

01:19:48.960 --> 01:19:53.560
[Guest]: it to various people. And we were still not, I was still not satisfied with what the answer

01:19:53.560 --> 01:19:59.360
[Guest]: that I was getting. Then one of my friends, she's a poet, Azra Naqvi, I went to her one

01:19:59.360 --> 01:20:03.560
[Guest]: day and I said, Azra, can you please understand that? So she sat and she said reading. And

01:20:03.560 --> 01:20:09.400
[Guest]: then suddenly she said, you know, this isn't worse. So when she got the verse is when we

01:20:09.400 --> 01:20:17.480
[Guest]: were able to separate it. So we could then separate that. Okay, this title ends here.

01:20:17.480 --> 01:20:23.160
[Guest]: This one starts here. So after that, it became easy. And then when I told that to my Mufti

01:20:23.160 --> 01:20:27.880
[Guest]: Sahib, then he said, you know, and that he'd already told me, he said, one line is in Arabic

01:20:27.880 --> 01:20:33.280
[Guest]: and the same thing he said in Persian. And it was obviously a very, very hyperbolic kind

01:20:33.280 --> 01:20:40.280
[Guest]: of language that was used. So that was very difficult. And where is the part on the monuments

01:20:40.280 --> 01:20:45.560
[Guest]: took me, say, two years to do it, because I wasn't doing it full time. I was writing

01:20:45.560 --> 01:20:50.840
[Guest]: my book and doing this. But this part I did dedicated only to that it took me over a year,

01:20:50.840 --> 01:20:56.000
[Guest]: those hundred pages. Wow. And that and then also I had to leave out a lot of portions

01:20:56.000 --> 01:21:01.200
[Guest]: because the when he's talking about the poets and the ulemas, he gives their Persian and

01:21:01.200 --> 01:21:07.560
[Guest]: Arabic Qasidas and whatever. So since I don't know Persian, I was translating it from a

01:21:07.560 --> 01:21:13.200
[Guest]: historical point of view. So I kept only their biographies and whatever I thought was important

01:21:13.200 --> 01:21:18.080
[Guest]: for a student of history to know. And I've left a note in my introduction that I hope

01:21:18.080 --> 01:21:24.520
[Guest]: one day some Persian or Arabic scholar will translate the whole thing of this chapter

01:21:24.520 --> 01:21:31.280
[Guest]: because I'm sure the Qasidas and the description that whoever wrote would be very, very interesting.

01:21:31.280 --> 01:21:36.160
[Amit Varma]: And in all your studies, when you're reading all these really old documents, are there

01:21:36.160 --> 01:21:40.680
[Amit Varma]: enough of them for you to then get a sense of the evolution of the language through the

01:21:40.680 --> 01:21:45.680
[Guest]: centuries? In this book itself, the first book to the second book. Persianized Urdu

01:21:45.680 --> 01:21:51.440
[Amit Varma]: and the regular Urdu. Persianized to simple Urdu. Wow. So from one person. So, OK, so

01:21:51.440 --> 01:21:56.640
[Amit Varma]: my next question is a slightly complex one in the sense that today, you know, there are

01:21:56.640 --> 01:22:02.720
[Amit Varma]: so many debates about the idea of India, right? But the India itself is relatively recent.

01:22:02.720 --> 01:22:08.240
[Amit Varma]: Now, through your history of studying all the many different delis that have come up,

01:22:08.240 --> 01:22:12.520
[Amit Varma]: you have also come across, I don't know what's the phrase for it. I can't call it the many

01:22:12.520 --> 01:22:18.280
[Amit Varma]: ideas of Delhi, but sort of the many ideas of us as seen from Delhi, you know, the many

01:22:18.280 --> 01:22:23.440
[Amit Varma]: ideas of whoever lives in Delhi or what they are, what the society is like, you know. So

01:22:23.440 --> 01:22:28.520
[Amit Varma]: is it possible to say that there are sort of different ideologies and philosophies of

01:22:28.520 --> 01:22:34.360
[Amit Varma]: the state and so on evolving through these centuries? Or is it like very binary in the

01:22:34.360 --> 01:22:38.240
[Amit Varma]: sense of, OK, we are now the kings, we will destroy everything else, we will do our own

01:22:38.240 --> 01:22:44.560
[Amit Varma]: thing? Or is there something much more subtle and complex and assimilative happening there?

01:22:44.560 --> 01:22:49.160
[Guest]: Something much more subtle and assimilative. We have, on the one hand, we do have the kings

01:22:49.160 --> 01:22:54.000
[Guest]: who are destroying and who are rebuilding. But on the other hand, we have a Dargah of

01:22:54.000 --> 01:23:00.720
[Guest]: Hazrat Zamuddin where Basant is being celebrated. As I said, we have a Mughal king who is offering

01:23:00.720 --> 01:23:06.040
[Guest]: a Chadar at a temple in Mehrauli and saying that if I can't go to the temple, I will not

01:23:06.040 --> 01:23:13.200
[Guest]: go to the Mandir. You have Holi, Diwali, Rakhi being celebrated inside the Red Fort and there

01:23:13.200 --> 01:23:18.560
[Guest]: is a documented proof that Muhammad bin Tughlaq was celebrating Holi. Ibn Battuta, I think,

01:23:18.560 --> 01:23:27.800
[Guest]: talks of it. So you have all this and you have, you know, like, it's so complex. It's,

01:23:27.800 --> 01:23:32.120
[Guest]: you know, like when you talk of one period or you talk of one ruler, there are so many

01:23:32.120 --> 01:23:37.640
[Guest]: facets to it. Like now one of my favorite stories again is Muhammad bin Tughlaq. He

01:23:37.640 --> 01:23:43.440
[Guest]: was a tyrant. He is supposed to be an eccentric genius. He had so many of these master strokes

01:23:43.440 --> 01:23:49.400
[Guest]: that over the change of capital, the currency, you know, etc. etc. And in between, a lot

01:23:49.400 --> 01:23:54.800
[Guest]: of people died. So when his cousin Feroz Shah Tughlaq ascends the throne, what he does is

01:23:54.800 --> 01:24:00.040
[Guest]: that he was very fond of his cousin, obviously, and he never thought he'd be the king. Now

01:24:00.040 --> 01:24:05.720
[Guest]: he becomes the king. So he gets searches for all the descendants of the people that Muhammad

01:24:05.720 --> 01:24:11.680
[Guest]: bin Tughlaq had killed. And that's a story that's documented. And I think Sir Syed and

01:24:11.680 --> 01:24:17.760
[Guest]: Mashiruddin Ahmed both have documented. I've mentioned who have documented it in the book.

01:24:17.760 --> 01:24:22.680
[Guest]: I keep getting so much of information overload that I forget who's documented what. So he

01:24:22.680 --> 01:24:27.400
[Guest]: then gets these mafi namas from them, from the descendants, and he buries them next to

01:24:27.400 --> 01:24:35.160
[Guest]: the grave of Muhammad bin Tughlaq. May God forgive him. Wow. I thought he'd out of remorse,

01:24:35.160 --> 01:24:39.280
[Amit Varma]: he contacted them to make their lives better in some way, but no, he wanted the mafi namas

01:24:39.280 --> 01:24:46.280
[Guest]: for his brother. So this is how things happened then. So he's getting that. Whether he didn't

01:24:46.280 --> 01:24:51.000
[Guest]: make their life better or not, I don't know. He may have. But because he ruled for 50 years

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:56.400
[Guest]: and he was supposed to be a good king. But this is how so, you know, on one hand, you

01:24:56.400 --> 01:25:01.880
[Guest]: have that. On the other hand, you have that Muhammad bin Tughlaq also built the Satpula,

01:25:01.880 --> 01:25:07.120
[Guest]: which is an irrigation system so that the farmers could have, you know, water, easy

01:25:07.120 --> 01:25:14.760
[Guest]: water. So all this is also happening. And he was a very devoted devotee of Hazrat Ramuddin

01:25:14.760 --> 01:25:23.720
[Guest]: Ali. In fact, he is one of the few people who he held his beer in his funeral. So he

01:25:23.720 --> 01:25:29.960
[Guest]: had that aspect to him also. He was very cruel also. So you have all this. So every ruler

01:25:29.960 --> 01:25:35.640
[Guest]: has many aspects to it. And the people who are living also have obviously different.

01:25:35.640 --> 01:25:44.120
[Guest]: And the other thing is that this is Sahil Udhiyanvi. When we talk of Taj Mahal and today

01:25:44.120 --> 01:25:50.040
[Guest]: is Valentine's Day, so we talk of Taj Mahal, we talk of Mumtaz Mahal and Shah Jahan, of

01:25:50.040 --> 01:25:53.320
[Guest]: their love for each other. And Sahil Udhiyanvi says,

01:25:53.320 --> 01:26:10.040
[Guest]: The artisans must also have worked. Those whose, you know, their graves are unknown.

01:26:10.040 --> 01:26:14.960
[Guest]: So there are so many levels, so many aspects, and we can just keep on talking about the

01:26:14.960 --> 01:26:20.280
[Guest]: people who lived here. They are nameless. We don't even know where they are buried.

01:26:20.280 --> 01:26:24.160
[Guest]: They are dead and gone. The people who actually built the cities, we don't know about them.

01:26:24.160 --> 01:26:29.680
[Guest]: Now we do know the architects of Shah Jahanabad. They have mahalas named after them. Ustad

01:26:29.680 --> 01:26:35.400
[Guest]: Hira, Ustad Lahori, there are mahalas or areas in Shah Jahanabad which are named after them.

01:26:35.400 --> 01:26:40.400
[Guest]: But what about the people? We don't know them. What about the people who live there? We don't

01:26:40.400 --> 01:26:44.760
[Guest]: know much about them. We know the areas. We know that there is one Paiwala. Now Paiwala

01:26:44.760 --> 01:26:55.280
[Guest]: was because they sold bedsteads. Kinari Bazaar and Dareeba were the places where wedding

01:26:55.280 --> 01:26:59.880
[Guest]: shopping was done. Who were the people who got married? Who were the people who had happy

01:26:59.880 --> 01:27:04.600
[Guest]: marriages or whatever it is? These are things we have no idea about. So we, you know, history

01:27:04.600 --> 01:27:10.280
[Guest]: is, as they say, written only from one point of view at a time.

01:27:10.280 --> 01:27:13.800
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, that's what my next question was going to be about. But before we go there,

01:27:13.800 --> 01:27:18.400
[Amit Varma]: let me point out to my listeners, we are recording this on Feb 14th, which shows our dedication

01:27:18.400 --> 01:27:22.840
[Amit Varma]: to our work that Rana ji has come all the way from Greater Noida to Hauskas to talk

01:27:22.840 --> 01:27:28.320
[Amit Varma]: about history with me. And here I am recording in a studio far from home. And like you pointed

01:27:28.320 --> 01:27:34.200
[Amit Varma]: out, you know, in the 20th century and in the 19th century, even, it's very easy, relatively

01:27:34.200 --> 01:27:39.160
[Amit Varma]: easy to get a sense of the lives that common people lived. But earlier centuries, as you

01:27:39.160 --> 01:27:44.160
[Amit Varma]: said, a lot of the history is written from the point of view of the court and the rulers

01:27:44.160 --> 01:27:48.680
[Amit Varma]: and whatever. And some of it, in fact, is actually court history. And you have to then

01:27:48.680 --> 01:27:53.640
[Amit Varma]: dig deeper to find other reliable histories. But we don't really get a sense of how the

01:27:53.640 --> 01:27:58.280
[Amit Varma]: common people lived. And the history of all of these Delhi's that you've written about

01:27:58.280 --> 01:28:03.200
[Amit Varma]: also is not just a history of the tombs of these noblemen and these great monuments that

01:28:03.200 --> 01:28:10.160
[Amit Varma]: they built. But how much harder is it to then understand the lives of the common people

01:28:10.160 --> 01:28:12.240
[Amit Varma]: and how they lived and where they lived?

01:28:12.240 --> 01:28:18.160
[Guest]: So these descriptions come only from those very short stories that I've given of, there

01:28:18.160 --> 01:28:23.080
[Guest]: are a lot of these Urdu books, but written after the fall of the Mughal Empire. Like

01:28:23.080 --> 01:28:29.200
[Guest]: there's this book called Dilli ki ajeeb shakhsiyat, Dilli ki chand shakhsiyat. Now they talk about

01:28:29.200 --> 01:28:36.760
[Guest]: a kebab ji called Ghummi kebabi. And Ghummi used to be a cook in the Mughal kitchen. And

01:28:36.760 --> 01:28:42.200
[Guest]: he comes onto the roads after 1857 and he opens up his stalls and how he is very particular

01:28:42.200 --> 01:28:48.640
[Guest]: about that. Whoever comes has to be in line. He will only serve people as per the time

01:28:48.640 --> 01:28:52.400
[Guest]: that they've come and how he serves and how he talks.

01:28:52.400 --> 01:28:56.480
[Amit Varma]: So there was a time when Indians knew how to queue up.

01:28:56.480 --> 01:29:02.160
[Guest]: And today when I, you know, there is a favorite kebab wala of mine, which I go to in Mattia

01:29:02.160 --> 01:29:07.320
[Guest]: Mahal and that is the same area where Ghummi would have sat. And again that Babu bhai also

01:29:07.320 --> 01:29:11.920
[Guest]: does not, you know, like people have to queue up there. You may be, you may, you know, like

01:29:11.920 --> 01:29:18.640
[Guest]: you may be as sophisticated as somebody or you may be just an ordinary worker or a laborer.

01:29:18.640 --> 01:29:22.960
[Guest]: He does not differentiate. He will give you only as per the time that you've come there

01:29:22.960 --> 01:29:27.800
[Guest]: and given the order. So I love that about him. And the fact that he, you know, like

01:29:27.800 --> 01:29:33.160
[Guest]: he's so very egalitarian about his approach of whom he's serving and how he's serving.

01:29:33.160 --> 01:29:37.800
[Guest]: And if there's a big rush, he will not talk to you. He, there's no time for chit chat.

01:29:37.800 --> 01:29:43.120
[Guest]: Like once I was doing, I was, you know, like scouting around for a food show and I wanted

01:29:43.120 --> 01:29:47.720
[Guest]: to showcase him and I went to him and he said, see, I don't have time for all this. I said,

01:29:47.720 --> 01:29:51.640
[Guest]: you know, I said, you'll be on TV, you'll be shown all over the world. He said, mujhe

01:29:51.640 --> 01:29:56.440
[Guest]: farag nahi padta. Mere paas bohot kaam hai. Mere paas bhakt nahi hai. So there are these

01:29:56.440 --> 01:30:04.440
[Guest]: kind of characters also, but who are there, who are part, who make a city. But they, like

01:30:04.440 --> 01:30:09.640
[Guest]: I try to document as much, there's a machhli wala who sits next to him and he sells fried

01:30:09.640 --> 01:30:14.680
[Guest]: fish. I have not eaten his fried fish actually, but I've spent a long time talking to him

01:30:14.680 --> 01:30:19.760
[Guest]: because he likes to chat. So I asked him once, I said, he said, I'm a third generation or

01:30:19.760 --> 01:30:25.600
[Guest]: a fourth generation sitting here and selling. So I said, when everybody, because that area,

01:30:25.600 --> 01:30:30.160
[Guest]: a lot of people migrated to Pakistan, I said, why didn't you go? And he said, humare budhur

01:30:30.160 --> 01:30:34.960
[Guest]: ko ne ka, ke Jamna kaise jaayegi humaise saath, Jama masjid kaise jaayega, Qutub Minar kaise

01:30:34.960 --> 01:30:37.040
[Guest]: jaayega humaise saath, toh hum kaise chale jaaye.

01:30:37.040 --> 01:30:39.440
[Guest]: Oh, that's beautiful. So you get a sense of...

01:30:39.440 --> 01:30:43.680
[Guest]: So these are stories which I've documented. I find it so fascinating to talk to these

01:30:43.680 --> 01:30:51.600
[Guest]: people that they are the ones who actually are the... ke yahan ki mitti ye hai, they

01:30:51.600 --> 01:30:54.000
[Amit Varma]: are the ones who hold us all together.

01:30:54.000 --> 01:30:59.520
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the sort of disturbing things about the current times, very disturbing

01:30:59.520 --> 01:31:05.520
[Amit Varma]: things, is this sort of caricaturish view of the Indian Muslim, which is being spread

01:31:05.520 --> 01:31:10.160
[Amit Varma]: by the current political dispensation, mostly by people who've never had Muslim friends

01:31:10.160 --> 01:31:14.800
[Amit Varma]: or interacted with Muslims in any way. But it's a very caricatured view where it is assumed

01:31:14.800 --> 01:31:20.480
[Amit Varma]: that all Muslims are necessarily radicalized, and they are somehow conflated with Pakistan,

01:31:20.480 --> 01:31:24.880
[Amit Varma]: as if there is, you know, something that wrong with Pakistan to begin with, you know. And

01:31:24.880 --> 01:31:29.840
[Amit Varma]: is this sort of something that is just of this century? I mean, through the centuries,

01:31:29.840 --> 01:31:35.040
[Amit Varma]: has there been sort of this kind of caricaturish view of the Indian Muslim, this kind of...

01:31:35.040 --> 01:31:39.040
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, when one looks at the sweep of history, it seems very clear that everything

01:31:39.040 --> 01:31:43.840
[Amit Varma]: is very syncretic. And sure, you have all this violence, which is political violence,

01:31:43.840 --> 01:31:47.920
[Amit Varma]: which is happening at the level of the ruler destroying things and building things or whatever.

01:31:47.920 --> 01:31:50.160
[Amit Varma]: But how has society been in all this time?

01:31:50.160 --> 01:31:57.520
[Guest]: See, this thing started after 1857. The first war of Indian independence, as it's been called,

01:31:57.520 --> 01:32:02.080
[Guest]: I prefer to call it the uprising, because all of India did not participate in it. So

01:32:02.080 --> 01:32:08.480
[Guest]: when the uprising of 1857 took place, it was termed by the British as a Mohammedan conspiracy.

01:32:08.480 --> 01:32:12.880
[Guest]: And it's after that, that they went after the Muslims, because for them, it was the

01:32:12.880 --> 01:32:18.880
[Guest]: Muslims who rose against them. Although that is not a fact, it was across religion, across

01:32:18.880 --> 01:32:23.680
[Guest]: religion, people who went against him. And if you had Hazrat Mahal, you also had Lakshmibai,

01:32:23.680 --> 01:32:27.920
[Guest]: then you had Kumar Singh, if you had Azimullah Khan, you had Kumar Singh, you had in Delhi

01:32:27.920 --> 01:32:33.120
[Guest]: itself, you had so many people and the saying Vallabhgarh ke jo Raja Nahar the, you had

01:32:33.120 --> 01:32:37.600
[Guest]: a lot of people who were even punished and who were executed afterwards. So that's not

01:32:37.600 --> 01:32:41.680
[Guest]: a fact. But the thing is that that is what they saw, because the head of what they call

01:32:41.680 --> 01:32:46.400
[Guest]: the rebels or the Ghaddar was Bahadur Shah Zafar, they had crowned him, whom they exiled.

01:32:46.400 --> 01:32:52.000
[Guest]: So they termed it a Mohammedan conspiracy. So after that, and they also went after the

01:32:52.000 --> 01:32:58.800
[Guest]: ruling class and the Zambidars. And that is when the actual demonization starts. And there's

01:32:58.800 --> 01:33:02.560
[Guest]: a building here, which I have mentioned in my book also, there's a building here on the

01:33:02.560 --> 01:33:08.480
[Guest]: ridge near the university called the Mutiny Memorial. It was put up, I think, in 1864.

01:33:08.480 --> 01:33:15.840
[Guest]: On that, they give a timeline of the siege of Delhi. And they write on the 14th of September

01:33:15.840 --> 01:33:22.480
[Guest]: 1857, Kashmiri Gate is breached, then they talk of 17th September, the king flees the

01:33:22.480 --> 01:33:28.800
[Guest]: fort and then 20th, they say they have captured the Red Fort. And then they say 21st September,

01:33:28.800 --> 01:33:34.800
[Guest]: the city is emptied of the enemy. Now, when you read Dastan-e-Ghaddar, you know that the

01:33:34.800 --> 01:33:39.520
[Guest]: enemy that is emptying and the enemy that's running away are the Muslim noble or the land

01:33:39.520 --> 01:33:43.680
[Guest]: owners or the whoever it is we're running away from them. And then just below that,

01:33:43.680 --> 01:33:51.040
[Guest]: you have a plaque written by the Indian government, I think, in 100 years of 1857 were being celebrated,

01:33:51.040 --> 01:33:58.000
[Guest]: where they say that the term enemy refers to patriots. So it's there they started, that is how

01:33:58.000 --> 01:34:02.400
[Guest]: it was perceived. And for so many years, they were not allowed, the Muslims were not allowed

01:34:02.400 --> 01:34:07.840
[Guest]: to come back to Shahjahanabad. And Ghalib documents that in his Dastanbu when he's talking about that.

01:34:08.480 --> 01:34:13.760
[Guest]: So does, of course, Zaheer Dahilvi. Zaheer Dahilvi talks about how he went to Alwar, then Jaipur and

01:34:13.760 --> 01:34:18.720
[Guest]: all over the place. And then finally, he goes to Rampur. From Rampur, then he gets a Maafi Nama

01:34:18.720 --> 01:34:23.440
[Guest]: and he's allowed to come back only, I think, as late as 1864, he comes back to Delhi because

01:34:23.440 --> 01:34:28.080
[Guest]: at that time there was going to be a Delhi Darbar. And then they gave a general Maafi Nama to the Muslims

01:34:28.080 --> 01:34:32.400
[Guest]: and said, OK, you can come back. But they do not come back into their old positions.

01:34:32.400 --> 01:34:37.600
[Guest]: And then there is this book called Begmat Ke Aasu written by Khawaja Hassan Nizami, which talks of

01:34:37.600 --> 01:34:43.600
[Guest]: the whatever befell the Mughal prince and princesses, where they are now begging on the streets.

01:34:43.600 --> 01:34:49.600
[Guest]: And there's again a book which has taken the story is also written in Begmat Ke Aasu

01:34:49.600 --> 01:34:55.840
[Guest]: by Ahmed Ali, the book called Twilight of Delhi, where he talks of Darbar ho raha hai and the king is

01:34:55.840 --> 01:35:00.880
[Guest]: going out on an elephant. And there's this man on a wooden, a cripple on a wooden cart, who's

01:35:00.880 --> 01:35:06.000
[Guest]: a physically challenged person on a wooden cart, who's begging. And it turns out that he's a Mughal prince.

01:35:06.000 --> 01:35:14.560
[Guest]: So, you know, these are things which were very much happened after. And then 1811, now this

01:35:14.560 --> 01:35:21.600
[Guest]: demonization of the Muslims started not just in 1857. It happens much before that. It happens when

01:35:21.600 --> 01:35:28.560
[Guest]: James Mills writes the history of British India. When he writes that in 1811, he had never come to

01:35:28.560 --> 01:35:34.400
[Guest]: India. He did not come to India even during or after writing it. He classifies it as Hindu,

01:35:34.400 --> 01:35:40.880
[Guest]: Muslim and British period. Now, he talks of the Hindu period as the golden period. Muslim is now

01:35:40.880 --> 01:35:46.560
[Guest]: the barbaric period and the British period are the saviors. And then you have this Eliot and Dawson,

01:35:46.560 --> 01:35:51.440
[Guest]: where it gives in the preface itself. They say that they want to talk about how the

01:35:52.480 --> 01:35:58.560
[Guest]: the people of India have been saved by the British. So, this is a very systematic thing that happened

01:35:58.560 --> 01:36:04.720
[Guest]: then during the national movement and afterwards. Then this whole thing, there was a lot of attempts

01:36:04.720 --> 01:36:10.960
[Guest]: to finish that. Gandhiji tried very hard. And as I always keep saying, I said, I grew up in Nehru's

01:36:10.960 --> 01:36:16.800
[Guest]: India when we did not have this difference of a Hindu and a Muslim. I never ever felt I was a

01:36:16.800 --> 01:36:22.880
[Guest]: Muslim. Of course, I'm a practicing Muslim. I do my prayers five times a day, whatever I do.

01:36:22.880 --> 01:36:29.040
[Guest]: I did that at home. It was never something I wore on my sleeve. But past four or five years,

01:36:29.040 --> 01:36:33.760
[Guest]: there's never a day when I'm not reminded that I am a Muslim. Before that, my only identity was

01:36:33.760 --> 01:36:38.320
[Amit Varma]: that I'm an Indian. And you know, with the British, it was obviously the dual imperative of one divide

01:36:38.320 --> 01:36:44.080
[Amit Varma]: and rule. So it's a strategic thing that you're doing that. And to also, you know, it was a simple

01:36:44.080 --> 01:36:48.720
[Amit Varma]: narrative, which kind of explained a very complex country. So they went along with it that you have

01:36:48.720 --> 01:36:54.800
[Amit Varma]: Hindu period, Muslim period and so on. Now, the thing is, looking back in history, you know, I'll

01:36:55.600 --> 01:37:00.320
[Amit Varma]: just to declare my bias straight away, it is obviously tempting for me to look at history

01:37:00.320 --> 01:37:05.200
[Amit Varma]: and look at our syncreticism and look at our society and say that, you know, Hindus and Muslims

01:37:05.200 --> 01:37:09.600
[Amit Varma]: have always lived in peace side by side. But equally, you can cherry pick evidence and come

01:37:09.600 --> 01:37:14.240
[Amit Varma]: to the conclusion that there have always been sort of there are a between the two, you know,

01:37:14.240 --> 01:37:19.520
[Amit Varma]: and a lot of how an outsider a layman like me would look at this history is I would look at

01:37:19.520 --> 01:37:25.360
[Amit Varma]: through the lens of my own bias, as I stated, for something like this, which is obviously such an

01:37:25.360 --> 01:37:30.320
[Amit Varma]: emotive subject, and which obviously has so much resonance with our current lives in the world that

01:37:30.320 --> 01:37:35.520
[Amit Varma]: we live in. How do you negotiate this sort of history? And do you feel that there is sort of

01:37:35.520 --> 01:37:41.120
[Amit Varma]: a clear narrative and the divisions that are there today are perhaps sharper than, you know, I mean,

01:37:41.120 --> 01:37:45.360
[Amit Varma]: obviously, we've had incredibly sharp divisions during the troubled times of partition and the

01:37:45.360 --> 01:37:50.880
[Amit Varma]: years before and so on. But if you look through the centuries old history of Delhi, are these

01:37:50.880 --> 01:37:56.560
[Guest]: relatively new? The divisions were between the rulers and the ruled. They were not religious

01:37:56.560 --> 01:38:02.560
[Guest]: differences. It was, you know, the oppression was there, but it was of the ruler. It wasn't seen as,

01:38:02.560 --> 01:38:06.960
[Guest]: you know, that, okay, he's a Muslim, he's oppressing me or he's a Hindu, he's replacing.

01:38:06.960 --> 01:38:10.320
[Amit Varma]: And that was Nehru's point of view as well. In fact, that a lot of communal differences

01:38:10.320 --> 01:38:15.200
[Guest]: aren't really religious differences. And if you see the history of communal rights,

01:38:15.200 --> 01:38:20.960
[Guest]: there were only five communal rights during the Mughal rule that also after the 18th century,

01:38:20.960 --> 01:38:26.480
[Guest]: out of which the first was in Ahmedabad. And after that, you've, after independence and here,

01:38:26.480 --> 01:38:32.480
[Guest]: even during the time of Nehru, you've had many, during the Congress rule also, you've had so many

01:38:32.480 --> 01:38:38.560
[Guest]: communal rights. And of course, now you have open division. I will, you know, like I normally am

01:38:38.560 --> 01:38:45.600
[Guest]: normally I'm very guarded about what I say, because I try to always look on the optimistic side of it.

01:38:45.600 --> 01:38:51.120
[Guest]: But there is no doubt that there is an all out attempt now to create a division.

01:38:51.120 --> 01:38:56.880
[Guest]: That otherization is happening. And to create the other, you have to

01:38:59.040 --> 01:39:03.120
[Guest]: make a caricature out of the other. You demonize and dehumanize.

01:39:03.120 --> 01:39:09.040
[Guest]: And a person like me who keeps, you know, like who fits in well into every kind of this thing.

01:39:09.040 --> 01:39:14.080
[Guest]: So I do not fit into the narrative of either the right wing Hindu or the right wing Muslim.

01:39:14.080 --> 01:39:19.520
[Guest]: And I am trolled and I'm abused by everybody. So I'm called a kafir by the Muslims and I'm

01:39:19.520 --> 01:39:24.880
[Guest]: called a budhparastana jihadi by the Hindus. So, you know, this otherization is that bad

01:39:24.880 --> 01:39:33.680
[Guest]: that anybody who talks of syncretism is considered, you know, a person of non-grata in these days.

01:39:33.680 --> 01:39:39.680
[Guest]: Because that is what is standing in the way. Both of them say, of course, the Muslim right

01:39:39.680 --> 01:39:46.720
[Guest]: wing is nowadays very, I should say, is not very empowered because the way that I'm talking of,

01:39:46.720 --> 01:39:52.960
[Guest]: say, a few years ago. Today, of course, they have been very restrained in their responses.

01:39:52.960 --> 01:39:57.360
[Guest]: And it has been taken over as just now in Shaheen Bagh, where this,

01:39:58.160 --> 01:40:02.160
[Guest]: although that news turned out to be false, but initially when there was this report that

01:40:02.160 --> 01:40:06.880
[Guest]: the Deobandi, from some clerics from Deobandi saying that, you know, the Shaheen Bagh protest

01:40:06.880 --> 01:40:11.840
[Guest]: should stop. And this lady said, we are fighting for the constitution, not for religion,

01:40:11.840 --> 01:40:16.800
[Guest]: that we should listen to you. So the narrative has changed. People have taken over and they've

01:40:16.800 --> 01:40:21.600
[Guest]: taken over from the religious leaders and they're trying to chart their own destiny.

01:40:21.600 --> 01:40:24.960
[Guest]: But I'm just saying that, you know, this otherization was happening

01:40:26.000 --> 01:40:31.840
[Guest]: for a very long time. Today, it's happening from the Hindu right wing. It's happening

01:40:32.720 --> 01:40:38.640
[Guest]: very, very, it's very fast. Like, how should I say it?

01:40:38.640 --> 01:40:52.800
[Guest]: You recognize them by their clothes.

01:40:52.800 --> 01:40:53.440
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly.

01:40:53.440 --> 01:40:56.400
[Amit Varma]: So how do you recognize them by their clothes? How do you recognize me by my clothes?

01:40:56.400 --> 01:41:01.360
[Amit Varma]: And even the demonization of biryani, you know, which is like my favorite food.

01:41:03.920 --> 01:41:08.080
[Guest]: So I keep saying, I think the Mughal favorite food was khichdi. They did not eat biryani.

01:41:08.080 --> 01:41:13.200
[Guest]: The word biryani was not even coined then. The Mughals did not eat biryani. Biryani comes much

01:41:13.200 --> 01:41:16.000
[Guest]: later in the late 18th and 19th century.

01:41:16.000 --> 01:41:19.440
[Amit Varma]: And these people would not be wearing the clothes they wear if the Mughals hadn't come here.

01:41:19.440 --> 01:41:21.680
[Guest]: Where do you think Modiji's churidar kurta comes from?

01:41:22.560 --> 01:41:29.280
[Guest]: So pajama itself is brought by them, pajama. But if you see Nuskhai Shah Jahani,

01:41:29.280 --> 01:41:34.320
[Guest]: which has been translated by Mrs. Salma Hussain as, I think, the emperor's table.

01:41:34.320 --> 01:41:39.200
[Guest]: Shah Jahan was very fond of cholai ka saag, baigan ka bhurta, aloo ka bhurta. He's eating

01:41:39.200 --> 01:41:45.280
[Guest]: the thing, the word biryani then was called zere biryani. And he's eating paneer ka zere biryani.

01:41:45.280 --> 01:41:52.240
[Guest]: So all these things are there, but they never ate the biryani and meat that week,

01:41:52.240 --> 01:41:57.760
[Guest]: thing that they did. They were very fond of khichdi and they were vegetarian on many days

01:41:57.760 --> 01:42:01.440
[Guest]: of the week. So Aurangzeb was totally vegetarian.

01:42:01.440 --> 01:42:07.200
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, as was Hitler. But, you know, paneer biryani, frankly, I must draw a line and here

01:42:07.200 --> 01:42:12.640
[Amit Varma]: I will be judgmental about the past ki paneer biryani kaun khata hai. But, you know, and would

01:42:12.640 --> 01:42:17.200
[Amit Varma]: you also say, and again, I don't want to be guilty myself of romanticizing what's happening. But would

01:42:17.200 --> 01:42:23.440
[Amit Varma]: you also say that what Shaheen Bagh represents, for example, is a combination of the best of all

01:42:23.440 --> 01:42:30.400
[Amit Varma]: the centuries of Delhi in terms of people coming together in spite of their diversity and their

01:42:30.400 --> 01:42:36.480
[Amit Varma]: differences. And also a combination of that with this modern India, where we have this liberal

01:42:36.480 --> 01:42:42.400
[Amit Varma]: constitution and we want to live by sort of these values and this idea of India. Or am I romanticizing

01:42:42.400 --> 01:42:46.720
[Amit Varma]: it too much? Or do you see, you know, while all this othering which makes you despair is going on,

01:42:46.720 --> 01:42:52.240
[Guest]: do you also see some hope? I think what has happened in Shaheen Bagh happened very spontaneously.

01:42:52.800 --> 01:42:59.440
[Guest]: And it's just become such a beautiful movement of inclusiveness of, you know, and because it's

01:42:59.440 --> 01:43:04.080
[Guest]: controlled by the women, I think it has that certain touch to it, where that harshness is

01:43:04.080 --> 01:43:10.320
[Guest]: not there. And it's just beautiful the way they are doing it, the way they embrace everybody. And

01:43:10.320 --> 01:43:15.600
[Guest]: I've gone there a couple of times, the way the inclusiveness of including everybody and how

01:43:15.600 --> 01:43:22.880
[Guest]: everybody is coming and being, you know, like joining with them across religion. So it's nothing

01:43:22.880 --> 01:43:28.720
[Guest]: to do with now. It is, of course, it is their identity, which is at stake. And when you go there,

01:43:28.720 --> 01:43:32.640
[Guest]: there is no doubt that the maximum number of things that you see, the most of the people

01:43:32.640 --> 01:43:38.400
[Guest]: that you see will be wearing scarves and hijabs. But it's, you know, you don't, that's not the

01:43:38.400 --> 01:43:42.640
[Guest]: thing that comes to your mind. They are wearing hijabs or whatever, but you do not see them as

01:43:42.640 --> 01:43:47.520
[Guest]: Muslims. You see them as women who are sitting there, very strong women who are sitting there

01:43:47.520 --> 01:43:53.440
[Guest]: protesting against something which is a constitutional right. So I do see that even I

01:43:53.440 --> 01:44:02.640
[Guest]: romanticize it. It is something which is just spread all over. And when I was, once I was

01:44:02.640 --> 01:44:07.280
[Guest]: talking to them and I was telling them, I said, you know, that this is the continuation of Sultan

01:44:07.280 --> 01:44:13.040
[Guest]: Razia. After all, Razia also stood up for her rights and stood up for her people. And she stood

01:44:13.040 --> 01:44:20.320
[Guest]: up to the jahilgani who were trying to oust her. And her father did say that she is equal to 20 of

01:44:20.320 --> 01:44:27.600
[Guest]: my sons. So in Delhi, and then you had Jehan Ara, you had Zebun Nisar, you had a long list of women

01:44:27.600 --> 01:44:33.520
[Guest]: who have been strong. And if we take it, if we do take even Indraprastha as having been here at

01:44:33.520 --> 01:44:39.280
[Amit Varma]: some point of time, then you have Draupadi. And that's also interesting. You know, when you look

01:44:39.280 --> 01:44:44.800
[Amit Varma]: back at Indian mythology, for example, and you look at the stark contrast between Draupadi and

01:44:44.800 --> 01:44:51.920
[Amit Varma]: Sita, and Sita almost seems to represent the ideal Indian woman as per, you know, the dominant

01:44:51.920 --> 01:44:56.560
[Amit Varma]: political view today would have it where she's subservient to her husband, and she's all of that.

01:44:56.560 --> 01:45:01.920
[Amit Varma]: And Draupadi is incredibly rebellious and badass and independent and whatever, which kind of shows

01:45:01.920 --> 01:45:06.960
[Amit Varma]: you that it's, you know, Indian sanskar is not so simple to pin down. It's got all these different

01:45:06.960 --> 01:45:11.440
[Guest]: strands, you know, even within Hinduism. Also, like I think the whole of India watched Ramayana

01:45:11.440 --> 01:45:16.480
[Guest]: and Mahabharata very religiously. There was not a single episode I missed. And in Mahabharata,

01:45:16.480 --> 01:45:20.400
[Guest]: I must have watched multiple times because I have to love the dialogue, especially of Sri Krishna.

01:45:20.400 --> 01:45:26.800
[Guest]: So, but recently, I think it's three or four years now that when Amisha's book came out on Sita.

01:45:27.360 --> 01:45:32.880
[Guest]: So, there the Sita is very different from this Sita. His Sita is a warrior. She is, in fact,

01:45:32.880 --> 01:45:40.080
[Guest]: the defense minister of Mithila. And she's a warrior and she's the Vishnu. So, when I read

01:45:40.080 --> 01:45:45.440
[Guest]: that, you know, it opened a whole new world of Sita to me. Yes, she does accompany her husband,

01:45:45.440 --> 01:45:51.840
[Guest]: but she's the Vishnu and then she marries Ram and then Ram also becomes a Vishnu. But it is she who

01:45:51.840 --> 01:46:00.080
[Guest]: is a very strong character. And it's a wonderful book. I really love that. They show Sita as

01:46:00.080 --> 01:46:04.960
[Guest]: somebody, a very, very strong character, not as the submissive character that we were seeing,

01:46:04.960 --> 01:46:10.880
[Guest]: that we saw in the TV series. So, there are supposed to be a lot of versions of Ramayana.

01:46:10.880 --> 01:46:16.640
[Guest]: There are, I think, 300 versions or something like that. Many versions. So, every version is

01:46:16.640 --> 01:46:22.000
[Guest]: written from a different and I had met Amish while he was writing it. And he said that he

01:46:22.000 --> 01:46:27.520
[Amit Varma]: is consulting a version that has Sita as the main character in it. That's remarkable. And I've just

01:46:27.520 --> 01:46:31.760
[Amit Varma]: realized that I've taken up almost two hours of your time. So, but before we go, tell me a little

01:46:31.760 --> 01:46:36.880
[Amit Varma]: bit about, you know, what are you working on now? You know, you've done these books on Delhi,

01:46:36.880 --> 01:46:42.320
[Amit Varma]: you've translated these books. What keeps you going? What's your next project? How do you,

01:46:42.320 --> 01:46:44.160
[Amit Varma]: what do you look forward to when you wake up in the morning?

01:46:45.040 --> 01:46:52.240
[Guest]: I'm working on three projects at the moment. One is a book and two projects. I normally don't like

01:46:52.240 --> 01:46:58.960
[Guest]: talking in advance. I'm a little superstitious, let's put it about my work. But the one project

01:46:58.960 --> 01:47:05.760
[Guest]: that has already, it's finished and about to come is an app which I have done on for a group called

01:47:05.760 --> 01:47:13.520
[Guest]: Rest Bird, which they were outsourced by ASI. It's on monuments. It's where you can read and

01:47:13.520 --> 01:47:17.840
[Guest]: hear about it. There's a podcast and there are different descriptions. I've curated 12 monuments

01:47:17.840 --> 01:47:23.280
[Guest]: for them on that. So, that is something that I'm very, I worked on the whole of last year. I

01:47:23.280 --> 01:47:30.080
[Guest]: visited these 12 monuments and I did that. And there are two other projects I'm working on. One

01:47:30.080 --> 01:47:35.040
[Guest]: is, two are books. And there's a third, yes. And the third, which is another thing that I'm working

01:47:35.040 --> 01:47:41.920
[Guest]: on. Hopefully by May, there should be more clarity. Cannot wait. And before you go, I'd like

01:47:41.920 --> 01:47:46.720
[Amit Varma]: you to ask, like my listeners always keep saying that they discover so many books through the

01:47:46.720 --> 01:47:52.000
[Amit Varma]: podcast and they love it when my guests recommend books that they absolutely should read. So before,

01:47:52.000 --> 01:47:56.880
[Amit Varma]: without tying you down to a subject like Delhi or whatever, just recommend three books that you

01:47:56.880 --> 01:48:01.520
[Amit Varma]: think everybody should read. And you can't include your own books because I am recommending those.

01:48:01.520 --> 01:48:06.400
[Guest]: I think they're absolutely amazing. So, one book is Richard Eaton, India and the Persian Age.

01:48:07.200 --> 01:48:15.920
[Guest]: That definitely everybody should read. And the second book is Manu Pillay's Rebel Sultans.

01:48:15.920 --> 01:48:21.600
[Guest]: Rebel Sultans, yeah. And third is Ira Mukherjee's, I'll give you four. And third is Ira Mukherjee's

01:48:21.600 --> 01:48:25.120
[Guest]: Daughters of the Sun. And fourth is Mani Mukder's Allahu Akbar.

01:48:25.120 --> 01:48:30.720
[Amit Varma]: That's fantastic because I've already done episodes with Manu and Ira and I am doing an

01:48:30.720 --> 01:48:35.520
[Amit Varma]: episode next week with Mani Mukder. So I feel like I've covered much of the material. I shall

01:48:35.520 --> 01:48:40.400
[Amit Varma]: definitely pick up that Richard Eaton book. Rana, thank you so much for being so generous with your

01:48:40.400 --> 01:48:43.120
[Amit Varma]: time and more power to all the work that you do in future.

01:48:43.120 --> 01:48:46.960
[Guest]: I hope it turned out also the way you wanted it to.

01:48:46.960 --> 01:48:51.760
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's great. And my listeners will tell you that on Twitter that this was such a fun episode.

